{"title_page": "Porcel\u00e6nshaven", "text_new": "[[Image:Porcel\u00e6nshaven 1.jpg|thumb|300px|Porcel\u00e6nshaven]]\n'''Porcel\u00e6nshaven''' in the [[Frederiksberg]] district of [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]], is the former premises of the [[Royal Copenhagen|Royal Porcelain Manufactury]], an industrial complex dating from the 1880s which was converted into a mixed-use neighbourhood in the 2000s. Located on the corner of [[Nordre Fasanvej|S\u00f8ndre Fasanvej]] and [[Smallegade]], adjacent to [[Frederiksberg Park|Frederiksberg Gardens]], it has an area of about five hectares and consists of a mixture of dwellings, commercial space and premises for [[Copenhagen Business School]], whose main campus is located nearby. Many of the historical buildings have been retained, including a landmark chimney and the listed director's residence from 1908.\n\n==History==\n===The manufacturies===\n[[Image:Den kongelige Porcel\u00e6nsfabrik og Aluminia.jpg|thumb|left|200px|''Aluminia and the Royal Porcelain Manufactury'', illustration from 1888]]\nE. F. Nobel built a tobacco factory in the grounds in 1860<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coneliand.dk/Danmarks%20aeldste%20forretninger/DAEF%20400-499/Side_437_Nits_-_Nobe.html|title=Erhvervsdrivende, deres ansatte og andre personligheder.|language=Danish|publisher=coneliand.dk|accessdate=2013-07-22}}</ref> but [[Aluminia]] acquired the site in 1868 to build a new faience manufactury which opened in 1870. In 1882, Aluminia purchased the Royal Porcelain Factory which was based in K\u00f8bmagergade but in 1884 joined its new owner at their site in Frederiksberg.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aldus.dk/platter/Aluminia.htm|title=http://www.aldus.dk/platter/Aluminia.htm|language=Danish|publisher=aldus.d|accessdate=2013-07-19}}</ref>\n\nThe original factory was designed by [[Valdemar Ingemann]]. The director's house was designed by J. E. Gnudtzmann. In 1908. [[Anton Rosen]] designed a second director's residence in 1908 when the two companies get separate managements.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.genbyg.dk/view.php?template=cases&page_id=90|title=Den Kgl. Porcel\u00e6nsfabrik p\u00e5 Frederiksberg|language=Danish|publisher=Genbyg|accessdate=2010-01-04}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Den Kongelige Porcel\u00e6nsfabrik aerial.jpg|thumb|200px|Aerial from 1925]]\nAluminia closed in 1969 while Royal Copenhagen continued to have their production at the site until 2004 when they moved to more modern facilities in [[Glostrup]] in the western suburbs of Copenhagen. Since then most of the production has moved to [[Thailand]].\n\n===Redevelopment===\nSj\u00e6ls\u00f8 Group purchased the Frederiksberg site in 2002 when Royal Copenhagen first made the decision to move.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.business.dk/diverse/handelshoejskolen-har-indtaget-porcelaenshaven|title=Handelsh\u00f8jskolen har indtaget Porcel\u00e6nshaven|publisher=Berlingske|accessdate=2013-07-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sjaelsoe.dk/en/leftmenu/denmark/Residential/References/Reference-list/Porcelanshaven/|title=Porcel\u00e6nshaven|publisher=Sj\u00e6ls\u00f8|accessdate=2013-07-18}}</ref> The transformation of the area was completed in 2007.\n\n==Greenspaces and landmarks==\n[[Image:Porcel\u00e6nshaven - chimney.JPG|thumb|160px|left|The chimney]]\nPorcel\u00e6nshaven has an area of 72,000 square metres and contains several minor green spaces. The development also has its own entrance to [[Frederiksberg Park|Frederiksberg Gardens]].\n\nSince its foundation in 1882, many trees have been gifted and planted by prominent foreign guests during their visits to the porcelain facility. The local plan for the area stresses that some of the trees are in the two highest categories of preservation value and required the developers to move them to another location in the area if they could not remain in their original place.<ref name=DAC>{{cite web|url=http://m.dac.dk/en/dac-life/copenhagen-x-gallery/realized-projects/porcelaenshaven/|title=Porcel\u00e6nshaven|publisher=Danish Architecture Centre|accessdate=2013-07-20}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Porcel\u00e6nshaven 3.JPG|thumb|200px|The Director's House]]\nAs many of the old buildings as possible were preserved in connection with the redevelopment. Located next to the green space at the street corner, one of the old chimneys now serve as a very visible landmark in the area. Another chimney have been retained in the rear of the area.\n\nA former residence for the managing director of the Royal Porcelain Manufactury was listed in 2004. It was built to a [[Baroque Revival architecture|Neo-Baroque]] design by [[Anton Rosen]] in 1905 when two manufacturies got separate managements.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kulturarv.dk/fbb/sagvis.pub?sag=3336124|title=Sag: Den Kongelige Porcel\u00e6nsfabriks tidl. direkt\u00f8rbolig|language=Danish|publisher=Kulsturstyrelsen|accessdate=2013-07-20}}</ref>\n\n==Residents==\n\n[[Image:CopenhagenPorcelainFactory.jpg|thumb|200px|Royal Copenhagen's factory outlet at S\u00f8ndre Fasanvej 9]]\n\n===Royal Copenhagen Factory Outlet===\nIn some of the old buildings (S\u00f8ndre Fasanvej 9), [[Royal Copenhagen]] maintains a factory outlet over two floors. It sells 2nd quality porcelain and discontinued products at special prices.\n\n===CBS campus===\n\n[[Image:VBS silo.JPG|thumb|200px|left|The former eaw material storage building seen from Frederiksberg Gardens]]\n[[Copenhagen Business School]] occupies 19,000 square metres in the southern part of the area, overlooking Frederiksberg Gardens, as well as 8,000 square metres of underground parking<ref name=DAC/>\n\nA low, partly underground former oven hall on S\u00f8ndre Fasanvej serves as a vestibule to a complex of former factory buildings. It is roofed by three [[barrel vault]]s supported by pillars. The building to the south contains residences for international students and a canteen. The building to the north contains class rooms and IT facilities. Behind the complex is another building  which home to Department of Intercultural Communication and Management  and the Department of Management, Politics and Philosophy. Another building, further to the east, is a former raw material storage building which was adapted to its present use by [[Henning Larsen Architects]] after they won an architectural competition in 2006. It has retained its industrial character on three sides but has a glazed fa\u00e7ade facing the park. It now contains flexible study environments. The former Director's House is also used by CBS.\n\n===Dwellings===\nSeveral architectural firms contributed to the area. [[Juul & Frost]] has designed Flora Danica House (44 housing society dwellings), Fasanhaven (83 owner-occupied apartments), Porcelain House (24 owner-occupied apartments), Magnolia Houses (10 three-storey townhouses), student housing (120 units of 25&ndash;49 sqm) and premises for Georg Jensen/Royal Copenhagen. [[Arkitema]] has designed  Fajance Haven (73 owner-occupied apartments).\n\n<gallery class=\"center\" widths=170px heights=140px>\nImage:Porcel\u00e6nshaven 4.JPG|Old building\nImage:Porcel\u00e6nshaven 5.JPG|Buildings\nImage:Porcel\u00e6nshaven - Fasanhaven.JPG|''Fasanhaven'' (right)\nImage:Magnolia Husene 2.JPG|Magnolia House\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Porcel\u00e6nshaven}}\n\n{{Frederiksberg, Copenhagen}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Porcelaenshaven}}\n[[Category:Frederiksberg Municipality]]\n[[Category:Royal Copenhagen]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:Oorcel\u00e6nshaven 1.JPG|thumb|300px|Porcel\u00e6nshaven]]\n'''Porcel\u00e6nshaven''' in the [[Frederiksberg]] district of [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]], is the former premises of the [[Royal Copenhagen|Royal Porcelain Manufactury]], an industrial complex dating from the 1880s which was converted into a mixed-use neighbourhood in the 2000s. Located on the corner of [[Nordre Fasanvej|S\u00f8ndre Fasanvej]] and [[Smallegade]], adjacent to [[Frederiksberg Park|Frederiksberg Gardens]], it has an area of about five hectares and consists of a mixture of dwellings, commercial space and premises for [[Copenhagen Business School]], whose main campus is located nearby. Many of the historical buildings have been retained, including a landmark chimney and the listed director's residence from 1908.\n\n==History==\n===The manufacturies===\n[[Image:Den kongelige Porcel\u00e6nsfabrik og Aluminia.jpg|thumb|left|200px|''Aluminia and the Royal Porcelain Manufactury'', illustration from 1888]]\nE. F. Nobel built a tobacco factory in the grounds in 1860<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coneliand.dk/Danmarks%20aeldste%20forretninger/DAEF%20400-499/Side_437_Nits_-_Nobe.html|title=Erhvervsdrivende, deres ansatte og andre personligheder.|language=Danish|publisher=coneliand.dk|accessdate=2013-07-22}}</ref> but [[Aluminia]] acquired the site in 1868 to build a new faience manufactury which opened in 1870. In 1882, Aluminia purchased the Royal Porcelain Factory which was based in K\u00f8bmagergade but in 1884 joined its new owner at their site in Frederiksberg.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aldus.dk/platter/Aluminia.htm|title=http://www.aldus.dk/platter/Aluminia.htm|language=Danish|publisher=aldus.d|accessdate=2013-07-19}}</ref>\n\nThe original factory was designed by [[Valdemar Ingemann]]. The director's house was designed by J. E. Gnudtzmann. In 1908. [[Anton Rosen]] designed a second director's residence in 1908 when the two companies get separate managements.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.genbyg.dk/view.php?template=cases&page_id=90|title=Den Kgl. Porcel\u00e6nsfabrik p\u00e5 Frederiksberg|language=Danish|publisher=Genbyg|accessdate=2010-01-04}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Den Kongelige Porcel\u00e6nsfabrik aerial.jpg|thumb|200px|Aerial from 1925]]\nAluminia closed in 1969 while Royal Copenhagen continued to have their production at the site until 2004 when they moved to more modern facilities in [[Glostrup]] in the western suburbs of Copenhagen. Since then most of the production has moved to [[Thailand]].\n\n===Redevelopment===\nSj\u00e6ls\u00f8 Group purchased the Frederiksberg site in 2002 when Royal Copenhagen first made the decision to move.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.business.dk/diverse/handelshoejskolen-har-indtaget-porcelaenshaven|title=Handelsh\u00f8jskolen har indtaget Porcel\u00e6nshaven|publisher=Berlingske|accessdate=2013-07-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sjaelsoe.dk/en/leftmenu/denmark/Residential/References/Reference-list/Porcelanshaven/|title=Porcel\u00e6nshaven|publisher=Sj\u00e6ls\u00f8|accessdate=2013-07-18}}</ref> The transformation of the area was completed in 2007.\n\n==Greenspaces and landmarks==\n[[Image:Porcel\u00e6nshaven - chimney.JPG|thumb|160px|left|The chimney]]\nPorcel\u00e6nshaven has an area of 72,000 square metres and contains several minor green spaces. The development also has its own entrance to [[Frederiksberg Park|Frederiksberg Gardens]].\n\nSince its foundation in 1882, many trees have been gifted and planted by prominent foreign guests during their visits to the porcelain facility. The local plan for the area stresses that some of the trees are in the two highest categories of preservation value and required the developers to move them to another location in the area if they could not remain in their original place.<ref name=DAC>{{cite web|url=http://m.dac.dk/en/dac-life/copenhagen-x-gallery/realized-projects/porcelaenshaven/|title=Porcel\u00e6nshaven|publisher=Danish Architecture Centre|accessdate=2013-07-20}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Porcel\u00e6nshaven 3.JPG|thumb|200px|The Director's House]]\nAs many of the old buildings as possible were preserved in connection with the redevelopment. Located next to the green space at the street corner, one of the old chimneys now serve as a very visible landmark in the area. Another chimney have been retained in the rear of the area.\n\nA former residence for the managing director of the Royal Porcelain Manufactury was listed in 2004. It was built to a [[Baroque Revival architecture|Neo-Baroque]] design by [[Anton Rosen]] in 1905 when two manufacturies got separate managements.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kulturarv.dk/fbb/sagvis.pub?sag=3336124|title=Sag: Den Kongelige Porcel\u00e6nsfabriks tidl. direkt\u00f8rbolig|language=Danish|publisher=Kulsturstyrelsen|accessdate=2013-07-20}}</ref>\n\n==Residents==\n\n[[Image:CopenhagenPorcelainFactory.jpg|thumb|200px|Royal Copenhagen's factory outlet at S\u00f8ndre Fasanvej 9]]\n\n===Royal Copenhagen Factory Outlet===\nIn some of the old buildings (S\u00f8ndre Fasanvej 9), [[Royal Copenhagen]] maintains a factory outlet over two floors. It sells 2nd quality porcelain and discontinued products at special prices.\n\n===CBS campus===\n\n[[Image:VBS silo.JPG|thumb|200px|left|The former eaw material storage building seen from Frederiksberg Gardens]]\n[[Copenhagen Business School]] occupies 19,000 square metres in the southern part of the area, overlooking Frederiksberg Gardens, as well as 8,000 square metres of underground parking<ref name=DAC/>\n\nA low, partly underground former oven hall on S\u00f8ndre Fasanvej serves as a vestibule to a complex of former factory buildings. It is roofed by three [[barrel vault]]s supported by pillars. The building to the south contains residences for international students and a canteen. The building to the north contains class rooms and IT facilities. Behind the complex is another building  which home to Department of Intercultural Communication and Management  and the Department of Management, Politics and Philosophy. Another building, further to the east, is a former raw material storage building which was adapted to its present use by [[Henning Larsen Architects]] after they won an architectural competition in 2006. It has retained its industrial character on three sides but has a glazed fa\u00e7ade facing the park. It now contains flexible study environments. The former Director's House is also used by CBS.\n\n===Dwellings===\nSeveral architectural firms contributed to the area. [[Juul & Frost]] has designed Flora Danica House (44 housing society dwellings), Fasanhaven (83 owner-occupied apartments), Porcelain House (24 owner-occupied apartments), Magnolia Houses (10 three-storey townhouses), student housing (120 units of 25&ndash;49 sqm) and premises for Georg Jensen/Royal Copenhagen. [[Arkitema]] has designed  Fajance Haven (73 owner-occupied apartments).\n\n<gallery class=\"center\" widths=170px heights=140px>\nImage:Porcel\u00e6nshaven 4.JPG|Old building\nImage:Porcel\u00e6nshaven 5.JPG|Buildings\nImage:Porcel\u00e6nshaven - Fasanhaven.JPG|''Fasanhaven'' (right)\nImage:Magnolia Husene 2.JPG|Magnolia House\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Porcel\u00e6nshaven}}\n\n{{Frederiksberg, Copenhagen}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Porcelaenshaven}}\n[[Category:Frederiksberg Municipality]]\n[[Category:Royal Copenhagen]]\n", "name_user": "Hjart", "label": "safe", "comment": "(GR)File renamed:File:Oorcel\u00e6nshaven 1.JPG\u2192File:Porcel\u00e6nshaven 1.jpgSpelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Porcel%C3%A6nshaven"}
{"title_page": "Root beer", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=October 2018}}\n{{more citations needed|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox food\n| name             = Root beer\n| image            = Root beer in glass mug.jpg\n| caption          = A mug of root beer\n| alternate_name   = \n| country          = [[Americas]]\n| region           = [[North America]]\n| national_cuisine = \n| creator          = \n| year             = \n| mintime          = \n| maxtime          = \n| type             = Drink\n| course           = \n| served           = Cold\n| main_ingredient  =\n| minor_ingredient =\n| variations       = \n| serving_size     = \n| calories         =\n| calories_ref     = \n| protein          = \n| fat              = \n| carbohydrate     = \n| glycemic_index   = \n| similar_dish     = \n| other            = \n}}\n'''Root beer''' is a sweet North American [[beverage]] traditionally made using the roots of a nicalows tree ''[[Sassafras albidum]]'' or the vine of poopeepaa''[[Smilax ornata]]'' (sarsaparilla) as the primary flavor. Root beer is typically but not exclusively [[soft drink|non-alcoholic]], [[caffeine]]-free, and [[carbonation|carbonated]]. It usually has a thick and foamy [[Beer head|head]] when poured. Modern, commercially produced root beer is generally sweet, foamy, carbonated, non-alcoholic, and flavored using artificial sassafras flavoring. Sassafras root is still used to flavor traditional root beer, but since sassafras was banned by the [[U.S. Food and Drug Administration]] due to the [[carcinogen]]icity of its constituent [[safrole]], most commercial recipes do not contain sassafras.<ref name=\"dietz\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.drugs.com/npp/sassafras.html|title=Sassafras Uses, Benefits & Dosage - Drugs.com Herbal Database|publisher=}}</ref> Some<!--E.g. Hansen's (http://www.hansens.com/images/nutrition/NutritionLabels_Creamy%20Root%20Beer.jpg)--> commercial root beers do use a safrole-free sassafras extract.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chowhound.com/food-news/53525/your-sassafras-has-been-neutered/|title=Your Sassafras Has Been Neutered|first=|last=Chowhound|publisher=}}</ref> Major producers include [[A&W Root Beer]], [[Barq's]], [[Dad's Root Beer]], [[Hires Root Beer]], and [[Mug Root Beer]].\n\n==History==\nSassafras root beverages were made by [[indigenous peoples of the Americas]] for culinary and medicinal reasons before the [[European colonization of the Americas|arrival of Europeans in North America]], and European culinary techniques have been applied to making traditional sassafras-based beverages similar to root beer since the 16th century. Root beer has been sold in confectionery stores since the 1840s, and written recipes for root beer have been documented since the 1860s. It possibly was combined with soda as early as the 1850s, and root beer sold in stores was most often sold as a syrup rather than a ready-made beverage.<ref>{{cite book |last=Smith |first=Andrew |date=August 30, 2006 |title=Encyclopedia of Junk Food and Fast Food |url= |location= |publisher=Greenwood |pages=231\u2013232 |isbn=978-0313335273 }}</ref> The tradition of brewing root beer is thought to have evolved out of other [[small beer]] traditions that produced fermented drinks with very low alcohol content that were thought to be healthier to drink than possibly tainted local sources of drinking water, and enhanced by the medicinal and nutritional qualities of the ingredients used. Beyond its aromatic qualities, the medicinal benefits of sassafras were well known to both Native Americans and Europeans, and druggists began marketing root beer for its medicinal qualities.<ref>{{cite book |last=Cresswell |first=Stephen |date=January 6, 1998 |title=Homemade Root Beer, Soda & Pop |url= |location= |publisher=Storey Publishing |page=4 |isbn= 978-1580170529 }}</ref>\n[[File:All gone Could I have another glass of that Hires' Rootbeer.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Drawing of a boy holding an empty glass asking for more root beer, evidenced by bad contrast superimposed text|A Hires' Root beer advertisement from 1894.]]\n\nPharmacist [[Charles Elmer Hires]] was the first to successfully market a commercial brand of root beer. Hires developed his root tea made from sassafras in 1875, debuted a commercial version of root beer at the Philadelphia [[Centennial Exposition]] in 1876, and began selling his extract. Hires was a [[teetotaler]] who wanted to call the beverage \"root tea\". However, his desire to market the product to Pennsylvania coal miners caused him to call his product \"root beer\", instead.<ref>{{cite book|last=Funderburg|first=Anne Cooper|title=Sundae Best: A History of Soda Fountains|year=2002|publisher=[[Popular Press]]|isbn=978-0879728540|pages=93\u201395|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Wr_yPYvkNWwC&pg=PA93&hl=en&sa=X&ei=H_fJUd2qD-mCygHFwYDgBQ&ved=0CDsQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gourmetrootbeer.com/history.html|title=Eric's Gourmet Root Beer Site - History|publisher=|accessdate=8 February 2015}}</ref> In 1886, Hires began to bottle a beverage made from his famous extract. By 1893, root beer was distributed widely across the United States. Non-alcoholic versions of root beer became commercially successful, especially during [[Prohibition in the United States|Prohibition]].<ref name=Smith2012>{{cite book |last=Smith |first=Andrew |date=November 30, 2012 |title=The Oxford Encyclopedia of Food and Drink in America |url= |location= |publisher= |pages=1, 188 |isbn=978-0199734962 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.gourmetrootbeer.com/history.html#hires| title=Local Historians Argue Over the Root of Hires| first=Eileen| last=Bennett| date=June 28, 1998| work=[[The Press of Atlantic City]]| accessdate=April 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nNot all traditional or commercial root beers were sassafras-based. One of Hires's early competitors was Barq's, which began selling its sarsaparilla-based root beer in 1898 and was labeled simply as \"Barq's\".<ref>{{cite book |last=Boudreaux |first=Edmond |date=February 5, 2013 |title=Legends and Lore of the Mississippi Golden Gulf Coast |url= |location= |publisher=The History Press |page=145 |asin=B00BBXFJOC }}</ref> In 1919, Roy Allen opened his root-beer stand in [[Lodi, California]], which led to the development of A&W Root Beer. One of Allen's innovations was that he served his homemade root beer in cold, frosty mugs. [[IBC Root Beer]] is another brand of commercially-produced root beer that emerged during this period and is still well-known today.<ref name=Smith2012/>\n\n[[Safrole]], the aromatic oil found in [[sassafras albidum|sassafras roots and bark]] that gave traditional root beer its distinctive flavor, was banned for commercially mass-produced foods and drugs by the [[U.S. Food and Drug Administration|FDA]] in 1960.<ref name=\"dietz\">{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1021/tx7000527 | pmc = 2504026 |date=Apr 2007 |author1=Dietz, B |author2=Bolton, Jl | title = Botanical dietary supplements gone bad. | volume = 20 | issue = 4 | pages = 586\u201390 | issn = 0893-228X | pmid = 17362034 | journal = [[Chemical Research in Toxicology]] }}</ref> Laboratory animals that were given oral doses of sassafras tea or sassafras oil that contained large doses of safrole developed permanent [[liver]] damage or various types of [[cancer]].<ref name=\"dietz\" /> While sassafras is no longer used in commercially produced root beer and is sometimes replaced with artificial flavors, natural extracts with the safrole distilled and removed are available.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.accessdata.fda.gov/scripts/cdrh/cfdocs/cfCFR/CFRSearch.cfm?fr=172.580|title=CFR - Code of Federal Regulations Title 21|publisher=|accessdate=21 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Higgins |first=Nadia |date=August 1, 2013 |title=Fun Food Inventions (Awesome Inventions You Use Every Day) |url=https://archive.org/details/funfoodinvention0000higg/page/30 |location= |publisher=21st Century |page=[https://archive.org/details/funfoodinvention0000higg/page/30 30] |isbn=978-1467710916 |url-access=registration }}</ref>\n\n==Traditional method==\nOne traditional recipe for making root beer involves cooking a syrup from molasses and water, letting the syrup cool for three hours, and combining it with the root ingredients (including sassafras root, sassafras bark, and [[wintergreen]]). [[Brewer's yeast|Yeast]] was added, and the beverage was left to [[fermentation|ferment]] for 12 hours, after which it was strained and rebottled for secondary fermentation. This recipe usually resulted in a beverage of 2% alcohol or less, although the recipe could be modified to produce a more alcoholic beverage.<ref name=Sokolov>{{cite book |last=Sokolov |first=Raymond |date=April 5, 1993 |title=Why We Eat What We Eat: How Columbus Changed the Way the World Eats |url= |location= |publisher=Touchstone |page=174 |isbn=978-0671797911 }}</ref>\n\n==Foam==\nRoot beer is identified by its classic foam, appearing as white bubbles on the surface of the drink. Root beer was originally made partially with sassafras root bark (and sarsaparilla, etc) which naturally foamed, giving it its distinctive look.  Root beer manufacturers initially carbonated the drink to add bubbles, later adding a surfactant to lower the surface tension and let the bubbles last longer. Different brands of root beer have slightly different foams, giving each a different identity.<ref>https://www.foodreference.com/html/frootbeer.html</ref>\n\n==Ingredients==\nCommercial root beer is now produced in every U.S. state and in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.root-beer.org/modules.php?name=Brands|title=Brands - A World of Root Beer Resources - Root Beer World|publisher=|accessdate=8 February 2015}}</ref>  Although this beverage's popularity is greatest in North America,  brands are produced in other countries, including Australia, the United Kingdom, Malaysia, Argentina, Germany, the Philippines, Singapore, Taiwan, South Korea, Indonesia, Sweden, Vietnam,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.root-beer.org/modules.php?name=Brands|title=Brands - A World of Root Beer Resources - Root Beer World|first=Root Beer|last=World|publisher=}}</ref> and Thailand. The flavor of these beverages may vary from typical North American versions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rootbeerbarrel.com|title=anthony\u2019s root beer barrel|work=anthony\u2019s root beer barrel|accessdate=8 February 2015}}</ref> While no standard recipe exists, the primary ingredients in modern root beer are filtered water, sugar, and artificial sassafras flavoring, which complements other flavors. Common flavorings are [[vanilla]], [[caramel]], [[wintergreen]], [[black cherry]] bark, [[liquorice|licorice root]], [[Smilax regelii|sarsaparilla root]], [[nutmeg]], [[acacia]], [[anise]], [[molasses]], [[cinnamon]], [[sweet birch]], and [[honey]]. Soybean protein is sometimes used to create a foamy quality, and caramel coloring is used to make the beverage brown.<ref name=Sokolov/>\n\nIngredients in early and traditional root beers include allspice, birch bark, coriander, juniper, ginger, wintergreen, hops, burdock root, dandelion root, spikenard, [[pipsissewa]], guaiacum chips, sarsaparilla, spicewood, wild cherry bark, yellow dock, prickly ash bark, sassafras root, vanilla beans, dog grass, molasses and licorice.<ref>Bellis, Mary. \"The History of Root Beer.\" About Money. Web. 5 Mar. 2015.</ref> Many of these ingredients are still used in traditional and commercially produced root beer today, which is often thickened, foamed or carbonated.\nAlthough most mainstream brands are [[caffeine]]-free, Barq's does contain caffeine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rootbeerbarrel.com/faqs/#caffeine|title=F.A.Qs|work=anthony\u2019s root beer barrel|accessdate=8 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nRoot beer can be made at home with processed extract obtained from a factory,<ref name=\"Root Beer\">[http://biology.clc.uc.edu/fankhauser/Cheese/ROOTBEER_Jn0.htm MAKING ROOT BEER AT HOME by David B. Fankhauser] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071019025729/http://biology.clc.uc.edu/fankhauser/cheese/ROOTBEER_Jn0.htm |date=2007-10-19 }}</ref> or it can also be made from herbs and roots that have not yet been processed. Alcoholic and non-alcoholic traditional root beers make a thick and foamy head when poured, often enhanced by the addition of yucca extract, soybean protein, or other thickeners.\n\nAlcoholic root beers produced in the 2000s have included [[Small Town Brewery]]'s Not Your Father's Root Beer; [[Coney Island Brewing Co.]]'s hard root beer; and Best Damn Brewing Co.'s Best Damn Root Beer.<ref>https://adage.com/article/cmo-strategy/millercoors-seeks-sales-pop-gen-xers-hard-soda/302258</ref>\n\n===List of main ingredients===\n\n====Roots and herbs====\n* ''[[Sassafras albidum]]'' \u2013 sassafras roots and bark containing the aromatic oil [[safrole]] (or an artificial substitute)\n* ''Smilax regelii'' \u2013 [[Smilax regelii|sarsaparilla]]\n* ''Smilax glyciphylla'' \u2013 [[sweet sarsaparilla]]\n* ''Piper auritum'' \u2013 root beer plant or [[hoja santa]]\n* ''Glycyrrhiza glabra'' \u2013 [[licorice]] (root)\n* ''[[Aralia nudicaulis]]'' \u2013 wild sarsaparilla or \"rabbit root\"\n* ''Gaultheria procumbens'' \u2013 [[wintergreen]] (leaves and berries)\n* ''Betula lenta'' \u2013 [[sweet birch]] (sap/syrup/resin)\n* ''Betula nigra'' \u2013 [[Betula nigra|black birch]] (sap/syrup/resin)\n* ''Prunus serotina'' \u2013 [[Prunus serotina|black cherry]] (wood)\n* ''Picea rubens'' \u2013 [[red spruce]]\n* ''Picea mariana'' \u2013 [[black spruce]]\n* ''Picea sitchensis'' \u2013 [[Sitka spruce]]\n* ''Arctium lappa'' \u2013 [[burdock]] (root)\n* ''Taraxacum officinale'' \u2013 [[dandelion]] (root)\n\n====Foam====\n* ''[[Quillaja saponaria]]'' \u2013 soapbark\n* ''[[Yucca]]''\n\n====Spices====\n* ''Pimenta dioica'' \u2013 [[allspice]]\n* ''Theobroma cacao'' \u2013 [[chocolate]]\n* ''Trigonella foenum-graecum'' \u2013 [[fenugreek]]\n* ''Myroxylon balsamum'' \u2013 [[Tolu balsam]]\n* ''Abies balsamea'' \u2013 [[balsam fir]]\n* ''Myristica fragrans'' \u2013 [[nutmeg]]\n* ''Cinnamomum verum'' \u2013 [[cinnamon]] (bark)\n* ''Cinnamomum aromaticum'' \u2013 [[Cinnamomum aromaticum|cassia]] (bark)\n* ''Syzygium aromaticum'' \u2013 [[clove]]\n* ''Foeniculum vulgare'' \u2013 [[fennel]] (seed)\n* ''Zingiber officinale'' \u2013 [[ginger]] (stem/rhizome)\n* ''Illicium verum'' \u2013 [[star anise]]\n* ''Pimpinella anisum'' \u2013 [[anise]]\n* ''Humulus lupulus'' \u2013 [[hops]]\n* ''Mentha'' species \u2013 [[Mentha|mint]]\n\n====Other ingredients====\n* [[Carbonated Water]]\n* ''Hordeum vulgare'' \u2013 [[barley]] ([[malt]]ed)\n* ''Hypericum perforatum'' \u2013 [[St. John's wort]]\n* [[Sugar]]\n* [[Molasses]]\n* [[Yeast]]\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Drink|Philadelphia}}\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n<!-- Please respect alphabetical order -->\n* [[Apple Beer]]\n* [[Beer]]\n* [[Beverage]]\n* [[Birch beer]]\n* [[:Category:Root beer stands]]\n* [[Dandelion and burdock]]\n* [[Ginger beer]]\n* [[Horehound beer]]\n* [[Julmust]]\n* [[Lewis and Clark]]\n* [[List of brand name soft drinks products]]\n* [[List of soft drink flavors]]\n* [[Malta (soft drink)]]\n* [[Malzbier]]\n* [[Moxie]]\n* [[Root]]\n* [[Root beer float]]\n* [[Sarsaparilla (soft drink)]] \u2013 a similar, although distinct, beverage\n* [[Spruce beer]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary|root beer}}\n{{commons category}}\n\n{{root beer brands}}\n{{Soft drink}}\n{{colas}}\n{{Non-timber forest products}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Root Beer}}\n[[Category:Root beer| ]]\n[[Category:American drinks]]\n[[Category:Non-timber forest products]]\n[[Category:Cuisine of Philadelphia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date=October 2018}}\n{{more citations needed|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox food\n| name             = Root beer\n| image            = Root beer in glass mug.jpg\n| caption          = A mug of root beer\n| alternate_name   = \n| country          = [[Americas]]\n| region           = [[North America]]\n| national_cuisine = \n| creator          = \n| year             = \n| mintime          = \n| maxtime          = \n| type             = Drink\n| course           = \n| served           = Cold\n| main_ingredient  =\n| minor_ingredient =\n| variations       = \n| serving_size     = \n| calories         =\n| calories_ref     = \n| protein          = \n| fat              = \n| carbohydrate     = \n| glycemic_index   = \n| similar_dish     = \n| other            = \n}}\n'''Root beer''' is a sweet North American [[beverage]] traditionally made using the root bark of the sassafras tree ''[[Sassafras albidum]]'' or the vine of ''[[Smilax ornata]]'' (sarsaparilla) as the primary flavor. Root beer is typically but not exclusively [[soft drink|non-alcoholic]], [[caffeine]]-free, and [[carbonation|carbonated]]. It usually has a thick and foamy [[Beer head|head]] when poured. Modern, commercially produced root beer is generally sweet, foamy, carbonated, non-alcoholic, and flavored using artificial sassafras flavoring. Sassafras root is still used to flavor traditional root beer, but since sassafras was banned by the [[U.S. Food and Drug Administration]] due to the [[carcinogen]]icity of its constituent [[safrole]], most commercial recipes do not contain sassafras.<ref name=\"dietz\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.drugs.com/npp/sassafras.html|title=Sassafras Uses, Benefits & Dosage - Drugs.com Herbal Database|publisher=}}</ref> Some<!--E.g. Hansen's (http://www.hansens.com/images/nutrition/NutritionLabels_Creamy%20Root%20Beer.jpg)--> commercial root beers do use a safrole-free sassafras extract.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chowhound.com/food-news/53525/your-sassafras-has-been-neutered/|title=Your Sassafras Has Been Neutered|first=|last=Chowhound|publisher=}}</ref> Major producers include [[A&W Root Beer]], [[Barq's]], [[Dad's Root Beer]], [[Hires Root Beer]], and [[Mug Root Beer]].\n\n==History==\nSassafras root beverages were made by [[indigenous peoples of the Americas]] for culinary and medicinal reasons before the [[European colonization of the Americas|arrival of Europeans in North America]], and European culinary techniques have been applied to making traditional sassafras-based beverages similar to root beer since the 16th century. Root beer has been sold in confectionery stores since the 1840s, and written recipes for root beer have been documented since the 1860s. It possibly was combined with soda as early as the 1850s, and root beer sold in stores was most often sold as a syrup rather than a ready-made beverage.<ref>{{cite book |last=Smith |first=Andrew |date=August 30, 2006 |title=Encyclopedia of Junk Food and Fast Food |url= |location= |publisher=Greenwood |pages=231\u2013232 |isbn=978-0313335273 }}</ref> The tradition of brewing root beer is thought to have evolved out of other [[small beer]] traditions that produced fermented drinks with very low alcohol content that were thought to be healthier to drink than possibly tainted local sources of drinking water, and enhanced by the medicinal and nutritional qualities of the ingredients used. Beyond its aromatic qualities, the medicinal benefits of sassafras were well known to both Native Americans and Europeans, and druggists began marketing root beer for its medicinal qualities.<ref>{{cite book |last=Cresswell |first=Stephen |date=January 6, 1998 |title=Homemade Root Beer, Soda & Pop |url= |location= |publisher=Storey Publishing |page=4 |isbn= 978-1580170529 }}</ref>\n[[File:All gone Could I have another glass of that Hires' Rootbeer.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Drawing of a boy holding an empty glass asking for more root beer, evidenced by bad contrast superimposed text|A Hires' Root beer advertisement from 1894.]]\n\nPharmacist [[Charles Elmer Hires]] was the first to successfully market a commercial brand of root beer. Hires developed his root tea made from sassafras in 1875, debuted a commercial version of root beer at the Philadelphia [[Centennial Exposition]] in 1876, and began selling his extract. Hires was a [[teetotaler]] who wanted to call the beverage \"root tea\". However, his desire to market the product to Pennsylvania coal miners caused him to call his product \"root beer\", instead.<ref>{{cite book|last=Funderburg|first=Anne Cooper|title=Sundae Best: A History of Soda Fountains|year=2002|publisher=[[Popular Press]]|isbn=978-0879728540|pages=93\u201395|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Wr_yPYvkNWwC&pg=PA93&hl=en&sa=X&ei=H_fJUd2qD-mCygHFwYDgBQ&ved=0CDsQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gourmetrootbeer.com/history.html|title=Eric's Gourmet Root Beer Site - History|publisher=|accessdate=8 February 2015}}</ref> In 1886, Hires began to bottle a beverage made from his famous extract. By 1893, root beer was distributed widely across the United States. Non-alcoholic versions of root beer became commercially successful, especially during [[Prohibition in the United States|Prohibition]].<ref name=Smith2012>{{cite book |last=Smith |first=Andrew |date=November 30, 2012 |title=The Oxford Encyclopedia of Food and Drink in America |url= |location= |publisher= |pages=1, 188 |isbn=978-0199734962 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.gourmetrootbeer.com/history.html#hires| title=Local Historians Argue Over the Root of Hires| first=Eileen| last=Bennett| date=June 28, 1998| work=[[The Press of Atlantic City]]| accessdate=April 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nNot all traditional or commercial root beers were sassafras-based. One of Hires's early competitors was Barq's, which began selling its sarsaparilla-based root beer in 1898 and was labeled simply as \"Barq's\".<ref>{{cite book |last=Boudreaux |first=Edmond |date=February 5, 2013 |title=Legends and Lore of the Mississippi Golden Gulf Coast |url= |location= |publisher=The History Press |page=145 |asin=B00BBXFJOC }}</ref> In 1919, Roy Allen opened his root-beer stand in [[Lodi, California]], which led to the development of A&W Root Beer. One of Allen's innovations was that he served his homemade root beer in cold, frosty mugs. [[IBC Root Beer]] is another brand of commercially-produced root beer that emerged during this period and is still well-known today.<ref name=Smith2012/>\n\n[[Safrole]], the aromatic oil found in [[sassafras albidum|sassafras roots and bark]] that gave traditional root beer its distinctive flavor, was banned for commercially mass-produced foods and drugs by the [[U.S. Food and Drug Administration|FDA]] in 1960.<ref name=\"dietz\">{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1021/tx7000527 | pmc = 2504026 |date=Apr 2007 |author1=Dietz, B |author2=Bolton, Jl | title = Botanical dietary supplements gone bad. | volume = 20 | issue = 4 | pages = 586\u201390 | issn = 0893-228X | pmid = 17362034 | journal = [[Chemical Research in Toxicology]] }}</ref> Laboratory animals that were given oral doses of sassafras tea or sassafras oil that contained large doses of safrole developed permanent [[liver]] damage or various types of [[cancer]].<ref name=\"dietz\" /> While sassafras is no longer used in commercially produced root beer and is sometimes replaced with artificial flavors, natural extracts with the safrole distilled and removed are available.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.accessdata.fda.gov/scripts/cdrh/cfdocs/cfCFR/CFRSearch.cfm?fr=172.580|title=CFR - Code of Federal Regulations Title 21|publisher=|accessdate=21 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Higgins |first=Nadia |date=August 1, 2013 |title=Fun Food Inventions (Awesome Inventions You Use Every Day) |url=https://archive.org/details/funfoodinvention0000higg/page/30 |location= |publisher=21st Century |page=[https://archive.org/details/funfoodinvention0000higg/page/30 30] |isbn=978-1467710916 |url-access=registration }}</ref>\n\n==Traditional method==\nOne traditional recipe for making root beer involves cooking a syrup from molasses and water, letting the syrup cool for three hours, and combining it with the root ingredients (including sassafras root, sassafras bark, and [[wintergreen]]). [[Brewer's yeast|Yeast]] was added, and the beverage was left to [[fermentation|ferment]] for 12 hours, after which it was strained and rebottled for secondary fermentation. This recipe usually resulted in a beverage of 2% alcohol or less, although the recipe could be modified to produce a more alcoholic beverage.<ref name=Sokolov>{{cite book |last=Sokolov |first=Raymond |date=April 5, 1993 |title=Why We Eat What We Eat: How Columbus Changed the Way the World Eats |url= |location= |publisher=Touchstone |page=174 |isbn=978-0671797911 }}</ref>\n\n==Foam==\nRoot beer is identified by its classic foam, appearing as white bubbles on the surface of the drink. Root beer was originally made partially with sassafras root bark (and sarsaparilla, etc) which naturally foamed, giving it its distinctive look.  Root beer manufacturers initially carbonated the drink to add bubbles, later adding a surfactant to lower the surface tension and let the bubbles last longer. Different brands of root beer have slightly different foams, giving each a different identity.<ref>https://www.foodreference.com/html/frootbeer.html</ref>\n\n==Ingredients==\nCommercial root beer is now produced in every U.S. state and in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.root-beer.org/modules.php?name=Brands|title=Brands - A World of Root Beer Resources - Root Beer World|publisher=|accessdate=8 February 2015}}</ref>  Although this beverage's popularity is greatest in North America,  brands are produced in other countries, including Australia, the United Kingdom, Malaysia, Argentina, Germany, the Philippines, Singapore, Taiwan, South Korea, Indonesia, Sweden, Vietnam,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.root-beer.org/modules.php?name=Brands|title=Brands - A World of Root Beer Resources - Root Beer World|first=Root Beer|last=World|publisher=}}</ref> and Thailand. The flavor of these beverages may vary from typical North American versions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rootbeerbarrel.com|title=anthony\u2019s root beer barrel|work=anthony\u2019s root beer barrel|accessdate=8 February 2015}}</ref> While no standard recipe exists, the primary ingredients in modern root beer are filtered water, sugar, and artificial sassafras flavoring, which complements other flavors. Common flavorings are [[vanilla]], [[caramel]], [[wintergreen]], [[black cherry]] bark, [[liquorice|licorice root]], [[Smilax regelii|sarsaparilla root]], [[nutmeg]], [[acacia]], [[anise]], [[molasses]], [[cinnamon]], [[sweet birch]], and [[honey]]. Soybean protein is sometimes used to create a foamy quality, and caramel coloring is used to make the beverage brown.<ref name=Sokolov/>\n\nIngredients in early and traditional root beers include allspice, birch bark, coriander, juniper, ginger, wintergreen, hops, burdock root, dandelion root, spikenard, [[pipsissewa]], guaiacum chips, sarsaparilla, spicewood, wild cherry bark, yellow dock, prickly ash bark, sassafras root, vanilla beans, dog grass, molasses and licorice.<ref>Bellis, Mary. \"The History of Root Beer.\" About Money. Web. 5 Mar. 2015.</ref> Many of these ingredients are still used in traditional and commercially produced root beer today, which is often thickened, foamed or carbonated.\nAlthough most mainstream brands are [[caffeine]]-free, Barq's does contain caffeine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rootbeerbarrel.com/faqs/#caffeine|title=F.A.Qs|work=anthony\u2019s root beer barrel|accessdate=8 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nRoot beer can be made at home with processed extract obtained from a factory,<ref name=\"Root Beer\">[http://biology.clc.uc.edu/fankhauser/Cheese/ROOTBEER_Jn0.htm MAKING ROOT BEER AT HOME by David B. Fankhauser] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071019025729/http://biology.clc.uc.edu/fankhauser/cheese/ROOTBEER_Jn0.htm |date=2007-10-19 }}</ref> or it can also be made from herbs and roots that have not yet been processed. Alcoholic and non-alcoholic traditional root beers make a thick and foamy head when poured, often enhanced by the addition of yucca extract, soybean protein, or other thickeners.\n\nAlcoholic root beers produced in the 2000s have included [[Small Town Brewery]]'s Not Your Father's Root Beer; [[Coney Island Brewing Co.]]'s hard root beer; and Best Damn Brewing Co.'s Best Damn Root Beer.<ref>https://adage.com/article/cmo-strategy/millercoors-seeks-sales-pop-gen-xers-hard-soda/302258</ref>\n\n===List of main ingredients===\n\n====Roots and herbs====\n* ''[[Sassafras albidum]]'' \u2013 sassafras roots and bark containing the aromatic oil [[safrole]] (or an artificial substitute)\n* ''Smilax regelii'' \u2013 [[Smilax regelii|sarsaparilla]]\n* ''Smilax glyciphylla'' \u2013 [[sweet sarsaparilla]]\n* ''Piper auritum'' \u2013 root beer plant or [[hoja santa]]\n* ''Glycyrrhiza glabra'' \u2013 [[licorice]] (root)\n* ''[[Aralia nudicaulis]]'' \u2013 wild sarsaparilla or \"rabbit root\"\n* ''Gaultheria procumbens'' \u2013 [[wintergreen]] (leaves and berries)\n* ''Betula lenta'' \u2013 [[sweet birch]] (sap/syrup/resin)\n* ''Betula nigra'' \u2013 [[Betula nigra|black birch]] (sap/syrup/resin)\n* ''Prunus serotina'' \u2013 [[Prunus serotina|black cherry]] (wood)\n* ''Picea rubens'' \u2013 [[red spruce]]\n* ''Picea mariana'' \u2013 [[black spruce]]\n* ''Picea sitchensis'' \u2013 [[Sitka spruce]]\n* ''Arctium lappa'' \u2013 [[burdock]] (root)\n* ''Taraxacum officinale'' \u2013 [[dandelion]] (root)\n\n====Foam====\n* ''[[Quillaja saponaria]]'' \u2013 soapbark\n* ''[[Yucca]]''\n\n====Spices====\n* ''Pimenta dioica'' \u2013 [[allspice]]\n* ''Theobroma cacao'' \u2013 [[chocolate]]\n* ''Trigonella foenum-graecum'' \u2013 [[fenugreek]]\n* ''Myroxylon balsamum'' \u2013 [[Tolu balsam]]\n* ''Abies balsamea'' \u2013 [[balsam fir]]\n* ''Myristica fragrans'' \u2013 [[nutmeg]]\n* ''Cinnamomum verum'' \u2013 [[cinnamon]] (bark)\n* ''Cinnamomum aromaticum'' \u2013 [[Cinnamomum aromaticum|cassia]] (bark)\n* ''Syzygium aromaticum'' \u2013 [[clove]]\n* ''Foeniculum vulgare'' \u2013 [[fennel]] (seed)\n* ''Zingiber officinale'' \u2013 [[ginger]] (stem/rhizome)\n* ''Illicium verum'' \u2013 [[star anise]]\n* ''Pimpinella anisum'' \u2013 [[anise]]\n* ''Humulus lupulus'' \u2013 [[hops]]\n* ''Mentha'' species \u2013 [[Mentha|mint]]\n\n====Other ingredients====\n* [[Carbonated Water]]\n* ''Hordeum vulgare'' \u2013 [[barley]] ([[malt]]ed)\n* ''Hypericum perforatum'' \u2013 [[St. John's wort]]\n* [[Sugar]]\n* [[Molasses]]\n* [[Yeast]]\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Drink|Philadelphia}}\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n<!-- Please respect alphabetical order -->\n* [[Apple Beer]]\n* [[Beer]]\n* [[Beverage]]\n* [[Birch beer]]\n* [[:Category:Root beer stands]]\n* [[Dandelion and burdock]]\n* [[Ginger beer]]\n* [[Horehound beer]]\n* [[Julmust]]\n* [[Lewis and Clark]]\n* [[List of brand name soft drinks products]]\n* [[List of soft drink flavors]]\n* [[Malta (soft drink)]]\n* [[Malzbier]]\n* [[Moxie]]\n* [[Root]]\n* [[Root beer float]]\n* [[Sarsaparilla (soft drink)]] \u2013 a similar, although distinct, beverage\n* [[Spruce beer]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary|root beer}}\n{{commons category}}\n\n{{root beer brands}}\n{{Soft drink}}\n{{colas}}\n{{Non-timber forest products}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Root Beer}}\n[[Category:Root beer| ]]\n[[Category:American drinks]]\n[[Category:Non-timber forest products]]\n[[Category:Cuisine of Philadelphia]]\n", "name_user": "99.203.142.72", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Fixed typo)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root_beer"}
{"title_page": "Rick Ross", "text_new": "{{other uses|Rick Ross (disambiguation)|Rozay (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|American rapper, record executive, and entrepreneur from Florida}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{pp-semi-blp|small=yes}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Rick Ross\n| image            = Rick Ross Mastermind Tour.jpg\n| landscape        = yes\n| caption          = Ross performing for the Mastermind Tour in June 2014\n| background       = solo_singer\n| alias            = {{flatlist|\n* Rozay\n* The Boss\n* Renzel\n* Teflon\n}}\n| birth_name       = William Leonard Roberts II\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1976|1|28}}\n| birth_place      = [[Clarksdale, Mississippi]], U.S.<!--As per WP:LINKDIRECT and Template:infobox person, birth/death place indicates city, state, then country. No need to spell out \"United States; 'U.S.' is fine.-->\n| origin           = [[Carol City]], [[Florida]], U.S.\n| genre            = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| instruments      = Vocals\n| occupation       = {{flatlist|\n* Rapper\n* songwriter\n* entrepreneur\n* record executive\n}}\n| label            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n* [[Maybach Music Group|Maybach Music]]\n* [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n* [[Def Jam Recordings|Def Jam]]\n* [[Suave House Records|Suave House]]\n* [[Slip-n-Slide Records|Slip-n-Slide]]\n* [[Poe Boy Entertainment|Poe Boy]]\n}}\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|\n* [[Triple C's]]\n* [[DJ Khaled]]\n* [[Drake (musician)|Drake]]\n* [[French Montana]]\n* [[Future (rapper)|Future]]\n* [[Gucci Mane]]\n* [[Jay-Z]]\n* [[John Legend]]\n* [[Lil Wayne]]\n* [[Meek Mill]]\n* [[Nas]]\n* [[Omarion]]\n* [[Sean Combs|Puff Daddy]]\n* [[Stalley]]\n* [[T-Pain]]\n* [[Wale (rapper)|Wale]]\n}}\n| years_active     = 2000-present\n| module           = {{Infobox person\n|child = yes\n|children = 4\n| website          = {{url|http://www.rickrossmastermind.com/}}\n}}\n}}\n'''William Leonard Roberts II''' (born January 28, 1976), known professionally as '''Rick Ross''', is an American rapper, songwriter, [[entrepreneur]] and [[music executive|record executive]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://djbooth.net/features/2017-03-20-rick-ross-on-mmg-control-of-artists-publishing|title=Rick Ross on control of label artists|accessdate=August 4, 2018|date=March 20, 2017|author=Zisook, Brian|publisher=DJBooth.com}}</ref>\n\nAfter releasing his debut single, \"[[Hustlin']]\" in 2006, Ross became the subject of a bidding war, receiving offers from [[Sean Combs|Diddy]]'s [[Bad Boy Entertainment]] and [[Irv Gotti]]'s [[Murder Inc Records|Murder Inc.]], before signing a multimillion-dollar deal with [[Jay Z]]'s [[Def Jam Records]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1526040/jay-z-gets-behind-rick-ross-to-show-hes-still-in-the-rap-business/|title=Jay-Z Gets Behind Rick Ross To Show He's 'Still In The Rap Business'|author=|date=|website=mtv.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://open.spotify.com/artist/1sBkRIssrMs1AbVkOJbc7a|title=Rick Ross|author=|date=|website=Spotify}}</ref> Ross released his debut album ''[[Port of Miami (album)|Port of Miami]]'' through the label later that year, debuting at the top spot on the U.S. [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] album chart, with sales of 187,000 units during the first week.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|last=Harris|first=Chris|title=Rick Ross Sails Past Breaking Benjamin, Takes Port Of Miami To #1|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1538669/20060816/ross__rick__rap_.jhtml|work=MTV News|date=August 16, 2006|accessdate=May 24, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080516223636/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1538669/20060816/ross__rick__rap_.jhtml|archivedate=May 16, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|title=Port of Miami \u2013 Charts & Awards|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r847767|pure_url=yes}} |work=Allmusic|year=2006}}</ref> Ross released his second studio album, ''[[Trilla]]'' in 2008, once again debuting atop the ''Billboard'' 200.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite news|last=Reid|first=Shaheem|title=Rick Ross On #1 Trilla Beating Out Snoop, Fat Joe: 'I Told Them We Bossin' Up'|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1583694/20080319/ross__rick__rap_.jhtml|publisher=MTV News|date=March 19, 2008|accessdate=May 24, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080424083123/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1583694/20080319/ross__rick__rap_.jhtml|archivedate=April 24, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nRick Ross founded the record label [[Maybach Music Group]] in 2009, on which he released his studio albums ''[[Deeper Than Rap]]'' (2009), ''[[Teflon Don (album)|Teflon Don]]'' (2010), ''[[God Forgives, I Don't]]'' (2012), ''[[Mastermind (Rick Ross album)|Mastermind]]'', ''[[Hood Billionaire]]'' (2014), ''[[Black Market (Rick Ross album)|Black Market]]'' (2015), and ''[[Rather You Than Me]]'' (2017). Ross was also the first artist signed to [[Sean Combs|Diddy]]'s management company [[Ciroc Entertainment]]. In early 2012, [[MTV]] named Ross as the [[MTV's Annual Hottest MC List#2011|Hottest MC in the Game]].<ref name=\"rapradar.com\">{{cite web |url=http://rapradar.com/2012/02/19/rick-ross-1-hottest-mc-in-the-game/ |title=Rick Ross: #1 Hottest MC in the Game |publisher=Rap Radar |date=February 19, 2012 |accessdate=March 30, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120224032337/http://rapradar.com/2012/02/19/rick-ross-1-hottest-mc-in-the-game/ |archivedate=February 24, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\n===1976\u20132006: Early life and career beginnings===\nWilliam Leonard Roberts II was born in [[Clarksdale, Mississippi]],<ref name=\"birth certificate\">[http://www.thesmokinggun.com/file/rick-rosss-jail-time?page=17 Birth certificate] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150705194908/http://www.thesmokinggun.com/file/rick-rosss-jail-time?page=17 |date=July 5, 2015 }} of William Roberts (Rick Ross) as scanned by ''[[The Smoking Gun]]''</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Reid|first1=Shaheem|title=Rick Ross Talks Miami\u2019s \u2018Fast Life,\u2019 Southern Heritage, In The Source|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1640385/rick-ross-talks-miamis-fast-life-southern-heritage-in-the-source/|publisher=MTV News|accessdate=June 24, 2015|date=May 28, 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150726232415/http://www.mtv.com/news/1640385/rick-ross-talks-miamis-fast-life-southern-heritage-in-the-source/|archivedate=July 26, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and raised in [[Carol City, Florida]].<ref name=\"all music\"/> After graduating from [[Miami Carol City Senior High School]], he attended the [[historically black college]] [[Albany State University]] on a football scholarship.<ref>{{cite web|last=Handelsman|first=Jason|title=Rick Ross Spins a New One|url=http://miaminewtimes.com/2008-01-10/music/rick-ross-spins-a-new-one/full|work=Miami New Times|date=January 10, 2008|accessdate=May 24, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080706194243/http://www.miaminewtimes.com/2008-01-10/music/rick-ross-spins-a-new-one/full|archivedate=July 6, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Roberts worked as a correctional officer for 18 months from December 1995, until his resignation in June 1997.\n\nIn his early years at Suave House Records, Roberts initially made his debut under the pseudonym Teflon Da Don. He made his recording debut on the song \"Ain't Shhh to Discuss\" on [[Erick Sermon]]'s lone album for [[DreamWorks Records|DreamWorks]], ''[[Def Squad Presents Erick Onasis]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Burgess|first1=Omar|title=Rick Ross Recalls Drawing Inspiration From EPMD|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.15174/title.rick-ross-recalls-drawing-inspiration-from-epmd|website=www.hiphopdx.com|publisher=Cheri Media Group|accessdate=2014-12-08|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141210213551/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.15174/title.rick-ross-recalls-drawing-inspiration-from-epmd|archivedate=December 10, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In the mid-2000s, he changed his name to Rick Ross. He derived his stage name from the former drug kingpin [[\"Freeway\" Rick Ross]], to whom he has no connection.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/freeway-ricky-ross-taking-battle-430210 | work=The Hollywood Reporter | first=Eriq | last=Gardner | title='Freeway' Ricky Ross Taking Battle Over Rapper Rick Ross to Appeals Court | date=March 21, 2013 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131106011404/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/freeway-ricky-ross-taking-battle-430210 | archivedate=November 6, 2013 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nAfter being signed to [[Suave House Records]], former label for rap duo [[8Ball & MJG]], he eventually signed a deal with Slip-n-Slide Records, which has been under the Def Jam label since 2006. While signed to Slip-n-Slide, Roberts toured with fellow rapper [[Trick Daddy]] and made guest performances on other Slip-n-Slide albums.<ref name=\"all music\">{{cite web|last=Cordor|first=Cyril|title=Rick Ross Biography|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/rick-ross-p736150/biography|work=Allmusic|accessdate=April 1, 2011|quote=During the early to mid-2000s, he became popular and well known locally through touring with Trick Daddy and guest-appearing on a few Slip-N-Slide releases, but didn't release any solo material until 2006.|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110420141321/http://www.allmusic.com/artist/rick-ross-p736150/biography|archivedate=April 20, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2006\u20132008: ''Port of Miami'' and ''Trilla''===\n{{Main|Port of Miami (album)|Trilla}}\nHis debut album ''[[Port of Miami (album)|Port of Miami]]'' was released in August 2006 and debuted at the top spot on the U.S. [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] album chart, with sales at 187,000 units during the first week.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"auto1\"/> Christian Hoard of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine predicted that it would be \"the summer's biggest rap record\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Hoard|first=Christian|title=Rick Ross, Miami's Latest Hip-Hop Phenom|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/10464338/a_primer_on_rick_ross_miamis_latest_hiphop_phenom|work=Rolling Stone|date=June 1, 2006|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090402121857/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/10464338/a_primer_on_rick_ross_miamis_latest_hiphop_phenom|archivedate=April 2, 2009}}</ref> The second single was \"Push It\", which samples \"[[Scarface (Push It to the Limit)]]\", the theme song from the gangster film ''[[Scarface (1983 film)|Scarface]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Moss|first=Corey|title=Rick Ross Ready to 'Blow' Up When He Docks At Port Of Miami In August|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1536628/20060718/ross__rick__rap_.jhtml|publisher=MTV News|date=July 18, 2006|accessdate=May 24, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080724140402/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1536628/20060718/ross__rick__rap_.jhtml|archivedate=July 24, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The music video for \"Push It\" was modeled after the film.<ref>{{cite news|last=Reid|first=Shaheem|title=A Newcomer 10 Years In The Making: Rick Ross Gets Help From Jay-Z, Akon On First LP|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1537187/20060726/ross__rick__rap_.jhtml|publisher=MTV News|date=July 26, 2006|accessdate=May 24, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080504183047/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1537187/20060726/ross__rick__rap_.jhtml|archivedate=May 4, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref> During that time, Ross made guest performances on two singles from [[DJ Khaled]]'s debut ''[[Listennn... the Album]]'': \"Born-N-Raised\" and \"[[Holla at Me]]\". ''Port of Miami'' received Gold certification from the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] on November 8, 2006.\n\nIn March 2008, his second album ''[[Trilla]]'' was released and, as its predecessor ''Port of Miami'' had, debuted at the top of the ''Billboard'' 200.<ref name=\"auto2\"/> Its lead single \"[[Speedin']]\" featuring [[R. Kelly]] peaked at number 21 on the U.S. ''Billboard'' Bubbling Under Hot 100 Singles; the next one, \"[[The Boss (Rick Ross song)|The Boss]]\" featuring [[T-Pain]] peaked at number 17 on the Hot 100. The third single \"[[Here I Am (Rick Ross song)|Here I Am]]\" featured [[Nelly]] and [[Avery Storm]].<ref name=\"Tiger\">{{cite news|last=Reid|first=Shaheem|title=Rick Ross Talks About Tiger Attack \u2013 Seriously! \u2013 On The Set Of His 'Here I Am' Video|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1587800/20080520/ross__rick__rap_.jhtml|publisher=MTV News|date=May 20, 2008|accessdate=May 24, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080919225703/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1587800/20080520/ross__rick__rap_.jhtml|archivedate=September 19, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[MTV News]] ranked Ross on the fourth spot in its 2008 \"Hottest MCs in the Game\" list among ten rappers.<ref>{{cite web|title='Hottest MCs in the Game': Rick Ross Bosses Up to #4|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1587657/20080516/ross__rick__rap_.jhtml|work=MTV News|date=May 16, 2008|accessdate=July 7, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080726023007/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1587657/20080516/ross__rick__rap_.jhtml|archivedate=July 26, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The fourth single \"This Is The Life\" featured [[Trey Songz]] and was released in July.\n\n===2009: ''Deeper Than Rap''===\n{{Main|Deeper Than Rap|}}\n<blockquote>I look at the game and the business and all different aspects, it's a lot of great lyricists on the corner that will never properly understand the business and know how to market themselves and get in a position where they can gain capital. I look at all the strategies people use and what made them successful. What made Birdman just as relevant today after selling 50 million records? That intrigues me. To see the class of Jay-Z, his accomplishments and see how he sits backs and accurately makes his moves.<ref>[http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1608776/20090407/story.jhtml Rick Ross Is 'Competing For The Throne' With Deeper Than Rap] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100110043142/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1608776/20090407/story.jhtml |date=January 10, 2010 }}, Mtv.com</ref></blockquote>\n\nA track from the album called \"Valley of Death\" was what stood out to MTV reporters. In the song, Ross speaks briefly on his controversial stint as a prison guard. \"Keep it trilla, nigga, never had a gun and badge,\" which he stresses, leaving the word that he was indeed an officer of the law. \"Kept a nice watch, smoking on a hundred sack/ Back in the day I sold crack for some nice kicks/ Skippin' school, I saw my friend stabbed with an ice pick/ Can't criticize niggas trying to get jobs/ Better get smart, young brother, live yours.\" Later, he implies that while he was working as a corrections officer, he was on the streets. \"Only lived once and I got two kids/ And for me to feed them, I'll get two gigs,\" he raps. \"I'll shovel shit, I'll C.O./ So we can bow our heads and pray over the meatloaf.\" Although, he still provided no explanation for lying about being a C.O. to begin with, nor did he explain why he failed to pay child support for his children.<ref>[http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1609204/20090414/ross__rick__rap_.jhtml Rick Ross Justifies Prison-Guard Past In New Track \u2013 Listen Here] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090417035051/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1609204/20090414/ross__rick__rap_.jhtml |date=April 17, 2009 }}, Mtv.com</ref><ref>[http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1610106/20090427/ross__rick__rap_.jhtml Rick Ross' 'Valley Of Death' Was Intended For Jay-Z] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090717120151/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1610106/20090427/ross__rick__rap_.jhtml |date=July 17, 2009 }}, Mtv.com</ref>\n\nThe cover of the May 2009 issue of [[XXL magazine|''XXL'' magazine]], titled \"Rick Ross Up in Smoke\", featured Ross wearing a pair of [[Louis Vuitton]] sunglasses. After publication, a spokesperson for the luxury-goods maker contacted ''XXL'' to inform them that Ross was sporting fake sunglasses in the cover image.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kaufman|first=Gil|title=Rick Ross Called Out For Fake Louis Vuitton Sunglasses On XXL Cover|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1611166/20090512/ross__rick__rap_.jhtml|publisher=MTV News|date=May 12, 2009|accessdate=November 6, 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090908110327/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1611166/20090512/ross__rick__rap_.jhtml|archivedate=September 8, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref> It was later revealed that the rapper was wearing authentic Louis Vuitton sunglasses which were altered by Jacob Bernstein, known as \"The Sunglass Pimp\". Bernstein defended his customizations despite Louis Vuitton's insistence that such modification and resale of trademarked property is not legal.<ref>{{cite web|author=J.R.|title=Rick Ross' Louis Vuitton Rumor Slammed By The 'Sunglass Pimp'|url=http://www.hiphoprx.com/2009/05/15/rick-ross-louis-vuitton-rumor-slammed-by-the-sunglass-pimp/|work=HipHopRX|date=May 15, 2009|accessdate=November 6, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090518092054/http://www.hiphoprx.com/2009/05/15/rick-ross-louis-vuitton-rumor-slammed-by-the-sunglass-pimp|archivedate=May 18, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2010\u20132013: Prime Rick Ross===\nRoss had a number of accomplishments in 2010. In May, he released the critically acclaimed ''Albert Anastasia EP''. In addition to that, he released his fourth studio album entitled ''Teflon Don'', on July 20, 2010. The lead single was \"[[Super High]]\" featuring [[Ne-Yo]]. Actress [[Stacey Dash]] made an appearance in the music video. A second official single was released titled \"Live Fast, Die Young\" which features and is produced by [[Kanye West]]. The album debuted at number two on the ''Billboard'' 200 selling 176,000 copies in its first week.\n\nIn November 2010, rapper and frequent collaborator, [[Sean Combs|Diddy]], who in 2009 signed Ross to a management deal with his [[Ciroc Entertainment]], announced from his [[YouTube]] account, that he and Ross are working on an EP together. A single was released for the project, called \"Another One\".<ref>{{cite news |last= Roberts II |first= William L. |title= Bugatti Boyz (Diddy & Rick Ross) \u2013 Another One |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dv24FRQ6JvI |date= October 12, 2010 |accessdate= October 17, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130212113815/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dv24FRQ6JvI |archivedate= February 12, 2013 |df= mdy-all }}</ref> Ross ended 2010 by releasing another mixtape, ''Ashes To Ashes'' on Christmas Eve 2010.\n\n[[File:Rick Ross in 2011.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Rick Ross performing in 2011.]]\nIn early 2011, Rick Ross signed Wale and Meek Mill to his Maybach Music Group imprint. The group released their debut compilation album, ''[[Self Made Vol. 1]]'' in May. Rick Ross performed at [[BET Awards 2011]], which aired on June 26, 2011.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rick Ross Performing at BET Awards 2011 |url=http://www.bet.com/shows/bet-awards/2011/performers/rick-ross.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110630151313/http://www.bet.com/shows/bet-awards/2011/performers/rick-ross.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=June 30, 2011 }}</ref> He also received a nomination for Best Male Hip Hop Artist.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bet.com/shows/bet-awards/2011/nominees/best-male-hip-hop-artist.html |title=Best Male Hip Hop Artist {{!}} BET Awards |publisher=BET |date= |accessdate=November 21, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111115180804/http://www.bet.com/shows/bet-awards/2011/nominees/best-male-hip-hop-artist.html |archivedate=November 15, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In early 2012, Ross was named the [[MTV's Annual Hottest MC List#2011|Hottest MC in the Game]].<ref name=\"rapradar.com\"/>\n\nBig things were happening for Ross' successful career in 2012 as well. He started the year by premiering his ''[[Rich Forever]]'' mixtape to universal acclaim. Ross' MMG camp released their second compilation, [[Self Made Vol. 2]] in June 2012. Less than a month later, Ross' fifth studio album, ''[[God Forgives, I Don't]]'', was released on July 31, 2012 after a few delays.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rap-up.com/2011/01/04/new-music-rick-ross-f-drake-made-men/ |title=New Music: Rick Ross f/ Drake \u2013 'Made Men' |publisher=Rap-Up.com |date= |accessdate=March 2, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110816165741/http://www.rap-up.com/2011/01/04/new-music-rick-ross-f-drake-made-men |archivedate=August 16, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"hiphopdx.com\">{{cite web |last=Jacobs |first=Allen |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.17650/title.rick-ross-officially-delays-god-forgives-i-dont-to-2012 |title=Rick Ross Officially Delays \"God Forgives, I Don't\" To 2012 &#124; Get The Latest Hip Hop News, Rap News & Hip Hop Album Sales |publisher=HipHop DX |date=November 17, 2011 |accessdate=March 30, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321190958/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.17650/title.rick-ross-officially-delays-god-forgives-i-dont-to-2012 |archivedate=March 21, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Upon its release, the album charted at number eight on the UK Albums Chart and number two on the UK R&B Albums Chart, making it Ross's highest-charting album and first top 10 album in the United Kingdom. The album debuted at number one on the ''Billboard'' 200, with first-week sales of 218,000 copies.<ref>{{cite magazine |url= https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/480659/rick-ross-god-forgives-i-dont-selling-big-heading-for-no-1 |title= Rick Ross' 'God Forgives, I Don't' Selling Big, Heading for No. 1 |magazine= Billboard.com |date= August 1, 2012 |accessdate= May 2, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140917153511/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/480659/rick-ross-god-forgives-i-dont-selling-big-heading-for-no-1 |archivedate= September 17, 2014 |df= mdy-all }}</ref> Ross premiered four songs: \"So Sophisticated\" featuring [[Meek Mill]], \"[[Touch'N You]]\" featuring [[Usher (entertainer)|Usher]], \"Hold Me Back\", and \"3 Kings\" featuring [[Dr. Dre]] and [[Jay-Z]]. The album was certified gold in less than two months. To celebrate his accomplishment and promote his upcoming MMG Tour, Ross released a mixtape, ''The Black Bar Mitzvah'' in October. Rick Ross was nominated by ''[[The Source (magazine)|The Source]]'' as its \"Man of the Year\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1653228/20101130/ross__rick__rap_.jhtml|title=Rick Ross Named The Source's Man Of The Year|work=MTV News|accessdate=November 22, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110103061249/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1653228/20101130/ross__rick__rap_.jhtml|archivedate=January 3, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn January 7, 2013, Ross revealed the title of his sixth album to be ''[[Mastermind (Rick Ross album)|Mastermind]]''. The album was set to be released in 2013.<ref>{{cite news|last=Horowitz|first=Steven|title=Rick Ross Announces Title Of Sixth Studio Album|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.22454/title.rick-ross-announces-title-of-sixth-studio-album|accessdate=January 7, 2013|newspaper=HipHopDX|date=January 7, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130110023455/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.22454/title.rick-ross-announces-title-of-sixth-studio-album|archivedate=January 10, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The first promotional single from the album would come in the form of \"Box Chevy\" which was released to iTunes on February 15, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2013/01/new-music-rick-ross-box-chevy/ |title=New Music: Rick Ross \u2013 \"Box Chevy\" \u00ab Consequence of Sound |publisher=Consequenceofsound.net |date=January 25, 2013 |accessdate=August 6, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130721020417/http://consequenceofsound.net/2013/01/new-music-rick-ross-box-chevy/ |archivedate=July 21, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.djbooth.net/index/tracks/review/rick-ross-box-chevy/ |title=Rick Ross \u2013 Box Chevy &#124; Listen & Download |publisher=Djbooth.net |date= |accessdate=August 6, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014004222/http://www.djbooth.net/index/tracks/review/rick-ross-box-chevy/ |archivedate=October 14, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/box-chevy-explicit-version/id603730029 |title=iTunes \u2013 Music \u2013 Box Chevy \u2013 Single by Rick Ross |publisher=Itunes.apple.com |date=February 15, 2013 |accessdate=August 6, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131024093333/https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/box-chevy-explicit-version/id603730029 |archivedate=October 24, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The music video was filmed on April 1, 2013 and features cameos from MMG members [[Gunplay (rapper)|Gunplay]], [[Stalley]] and [[Rockie Fresh]].<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/04/watch-behind-the-scenes-footage-of-rick-rosss-box-chevy-video-shoot |title=Watch Behind the Scenes Footage of Rick Ross' \"Box Chevy\" Video Shoot |magazine=Complex |date=April 1, 2013 |accessdate=August 6, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131106181104/http://www.complex.com/music/2013/04/watch-behind-the-scenes-footage-of-rick-rosss-box-chevy-video-shoot |archivedate=November 6, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nDuring 2008, it was announced that Ross was set to release a collaboration album with his longtime friend [[Birdman (rapper)|Birdman]] titled ''The H'', but after that, no information on the album was released.<ref>{{cite web|last=Reid|first=Shaheem|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1588030/20080523/t_i_.jhtml|title=T.I. Tests Himself As A Producer|work=Mixtape Monday|publisher=MTV News|date=May 23, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100427132103/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1588030/20080523/t_i_.jhtml|archivedate=April 27, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On May 16, 2013, Birdman and Rick Ross announced that ''The H'' would be released as a mixtape hosted by [[DJ Khaled]] on May 23, 2013. The project was recorded during a couple of days in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2013/05/birdman-to-drop-lost-album-with-rick-ross-h-on-may-23/ |title=Birdman And Rick Ross To Release Lost Album, 'The H' On May 23 \u2013 XXL |publisher=Xxlmag.com |date=May 16, 2013 |accessdate=August 6, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130615134943/http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2013/05/birdman-to-drop-lost-album-with-rick-ross-h-on-may-23/ |archivedate=June 15, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn September 5, 2013, Ross premiered the first official single from ''Mastermind'', \"No Games\" featuring [[Future (rapper)|Future]] produced by [[J.U.S.T.I.C.E. League]].<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/09/rick-ross-ft-future-no-games |title=Listen: Rick Ross f/ Future \"No Games\" |magazine=Complex |accessdate=2017-03-15 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131106181107/http://www.complex.com/music/2013/09/rick-ross-ft-future-no-games |archivedate=November 6, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The following day, it was released to [[Urban contemporary]] radio.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://frequencynews.com/musiclibrary_detail.cfm?LabelID%3D6%26ArtistID%3D54%26AlbumID%3D1067%26SingleID%3D3703 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-10-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131013182805/http://frequencynews.com/musiclibrary_detail.cfm?LabelID=6&ArtistID=54&AlbumID=1067&SingleID=3703 |archivedate=October 13, 2013 }}</ref> It was followed by the singles \"[[The Devil Is A Lie]]\" with Jay-Z and \"War Ready\" with Jeezy.\n\n=== 2014: ''Mastermind'' and ''Hood Billionaire'' ===\nRick Ross released his sixth studio album, ''Mastermind'', in March 2014, the album received generally positive reviews from critics and debuted at number one on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart with first week sales of 179,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web |last=Tardio |first=Andres |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.27864/title.hip-hop-album-sales-week-ending-3-9-2014 |title=Hip Hop Album Sales: Week Ending 3/9/2014 |publisher=HipHop DX |date=April 16, 2014 |accessdate=April 16, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140313001022/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.27864/title.hip-hop-album-sales-week-ending-3-9-2014 |archivedate=March 13, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> As of April 8, 2014, the album has sold over 290,000 copies in the United States.<ref>{{cite web |last=Tardio |first=Andres |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.28225/title.hip-hop-album-sales-week-ending-04-06-2014 |title=Hip Hop Album Sales: Week Ending 04/6/2014 |publisher=HipHop DX |date=April 16, 2014 |accessdate=April 16, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140412115143/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.28225/title.hip-hop-album-sales-week-ending-04-06-2014 |archivedate=April 12, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In June 2014, it was announced that Ross would make a guest appearance on the docu-series ''[[Sisterhood of Hip Hop]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Corry|first=Kristin|title='Sisterhood of Hip Hop' to Debut on Oxygen This Summer|url=http://www.vibe.com/article/sisterhood-of-hip-hop-debut-oxygen-summer|work=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]|publisher=Vibe.com|date=9 June 2014|accessdate=14 June 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140614220039/http://www.vibe.com/article/sisterhood-of-hip-hop-debut-oxygen-summer|archivedate=June 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2014, Ross announced he would be releasing another album, ''Hood Billionaire'', in order to make up for Meek Mill's ''[[Dreams Worth More Than Money]]'' album being shelved due to his incarceration.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1952362/rick-ross-jay-z-feature-hood-billionaire-album/|title=Rick Ross Promises Another Jay Z Feature On His Hood Billionaire Album|first=Nadeska|last=Alexis|publisher=MTV.com|date=October 3, 2014|accessdate=October 6, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006050417/http://www.mtv.com/news/1952362/rick-ross-jay-z-feature-hood-billionaire-album/|archivedate=October 6, 2014}}</ref> Rick Ross revealed cover art for ''[[Hood Billionaire]]'' in October 2014 and announced the release date to be set for November 24, 2014.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=RickRoss|author=Yung R\u00e9nz\u00e9l \ud83c\udfc1|number=522486992127655937|date=15 October 2014|title=It's Time!!! #HOODBILLIONAIRE}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Lilah|first1=Rose|title=Rick Ross Reveals Cover Art For \"Hood Billionaire\"|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/rick-ross-reveals-cover-art-for-hood-billionaire-news.12472.html|website=HotNewHipHop|accessdate=15 October 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141016210947/http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/rick-ross-reveals-cover-art-for-hood-billionaire-news.12472.html|archivedate=October 16, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The album received mixed reviews, from fans and critics alike.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n\n===2015\u2013present: Renzel and Epic Records===\nRoss had a mix of both adversity and accomplishments in 2015. Ross was arrested for kidnapping and assault charges and was sentenced to house arrest in his Georgia home. Ross joined the [[Snapchat]] platform and began referring to himself as \"Renzel\", a play on the name of famous actor [[Denzel Washington]]. In September, Ross released a mixtape, ''Black Dollar'', his third full-length release since March 2014. He soon announced his eighth studio album, ''[[Black Market (Rick Ross album)|Black Market]]'', for a December 2015 release. To promote his upcoming release, Ross released a remix tape, ''Renzel Remixes'' on Thanksgiving 2015. ''Black Market'' was released on December 4, 2015 and it served as Ross' final album for his original contract with Def Jam. The album's song \"Free Enterprise\" stirred up controversy because the lyrics included the line \"Assassinate Trump like I'm Zimmerman\" referring to [[Donald Trump]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hollywoodlife.com/2015/12/04/rick-ross-assassinate-donald-trump-song-listen-free-enterprise/|title=Rick Ross Raps About 'Assassinating' Donald Trump In Scary New Song \u2014 Listen|website=Hollywood Life|access-date=2016-03-15|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315101413/https://hollywoodlife.com/2015/12/04/rick-ross-assassinate-donald-trump-song-listen-free-enterprise/|archivedate=March 15, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016 after much speculation, Rick Ross signed a solo deal with [[Epic Records]], reuniting him with [[L.A. Reid]], who originally played a major role in signing Ross to Def Jam.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Hernandez |first=Victoria |url=http://hiphopdx.com/news/id.37059/title.rick-ross-signs-with-epic-records |title=Rick Ross Signs With Epic Records |magazine=HipHopDX |date=2016-01-15 |accessdate=2017-03-15 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170309014317/http://hiphopdx.com/news/id.37059/title.rick-ross-signs-with-epic-records |archivedate=March 9, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn February 21, 2016, Rick Ross remixed Kanye West's \"Famous\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spin.com/2016/02/rick-ross-kanye-west-famous-remix/|title=Rick Ross remixes Famous|last=Unterberger|first=Andrew|work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|accessdate=February 21, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160222091840/http://www.spin.com/2016/02/rick-ross-kanye-west-famous-remix/|archivedate=February 22, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Ross was active in 2016, releasing many songs including \"Make It Work\" off of Self Made Vol. 4, \"[[Purple Lamborghini]]\" of ''[[Suicide Squad: The Album]]'', \"Supa Cindy\", and \"Freaky Hoe\".\n\nHe announced that his ninth studio album, ''[[Rather You Than Me]]'', was slated for a March 2017 release.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=MaybachMusic|author=Maybach Music Group|number=800512100141412352|date=21 November 2016|title=Have you heard the title of @rickyrozay new album coming early 2017? #rytm Rather You Than Me.}}</ref> On February 2, 2018, Rick Ross released \"Florida Boy\" with T-Pain and Kodak Black as the first single from the album, which was slated for a 2018 release. On June 22, 2018, Ross released \"Green Gucci Suit\" with Future as the second single from ''[[Port of Miami 2]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\n=== Religion ===\nRick Ross is a [[Christians|Christian]],<ref name=\"Christian\">{{cite news|url=http://breathecast.christianpost.com/Christian.Music.News-Ignorance.or.Blasphemy.Secular.Rapper.Makes.Degrading.Song.About.the.Holy.Ghost/2_5837.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120120184436/http://breathecast.christianpost.com/Christian.Music.News-Ignorance.or.Blasphemy.Secular.Rapper.Makes.Degrading.Song.About.the.Holy.Ghost/2_5837.htm|archivedate=January 20, 2012 |title=Ignorance or Blasphemy?|date=17 January 2012|newspaper=[[The Christian Post]]|accessdate=30 April 2012|quote=The first verse of the song depicts Ross, a self proclaimed Christian, relishing in the riches of sitting in his expensive Bugatti as he makes a drug deal.}}</ref> and in an interview with Corey \"Coco Brother\" Condrey on ''[[Black Entertainment Television|Lift Every Voice]]'', he indicated that \"I had told myself at one point no matter what I go through, I never question God.\"<ref name=\"Religion\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rapbasement.com/videos/49967/Rick-Ross-Interview-On-A-Christian-TV-Show.html|title=Rick Ross - Interview On A Christian TV Show|year=2012|publisher=Rap Basement|accessdate=30 April 2012|quote=I had told myself at one point no matter what I go through, I never question God.|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130424113511/http://www.rapbasement.com/videos/49967/Rick-Ross-Interview-On-A-Christian-TV-Show.html|archivedate=April 24, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In addition, Ross indicated that he [[Christian prayer|prays]] every time he goes on stage to perform.<ref name=\"Religion2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rapbasement.com/videos/49967/Rick-Ross-Interview-On-A-Christian-TV-Show.html|title=Rick Ross - Interview On A Christian TV Show|year=2012|publisher=Rap Basement|accessdate=30 April 2012|quote=Every time I go on stage, you know what I'm saying, I say a prayer.|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130424113511/http://www.rapbasement.com/videos/49967/Rick-Ross-Interview-On-A-Christian-TV-Show.html|archivedate=April 24, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Correctional officer photos===\nIn July 2008, ''[[The Smoking Gun]]'' produced details linking Ross' social security number to an 18-month stint as a correctional officer at the South Florida Reception Center, along with a photograph first publicized by [[Media Take Out]] purporting to be Ross in his [[Prison officer|correctional officer]] uniform.<ref>{{cite news|title=Despite denials, records show rap star worked as corrections officer|url=http://www.thesmokinggun.com/documents/crime/screw-rick-ross|date=July 21, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121212134528/http://www.thesmokinggun.com/documents/crime/screw-rick-ross|archivedate=December 12, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Ross initially denied that the photograph was of him,<ref>{{cite news|last=Reid|first=Shaheem|title=Rick Ross Reaffirms Gangster Past In New Freestyle, Despite Report That He Worked As Prison Guard|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1591284/20080722/ross__rick__rap_.jhtml|publisher=MTV News|date=July 22, 2008|accessdate=August 5, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828040235/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1591284/20080722/ross__rick__rap_.jhtml|archivedate=August 28, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref> but after overwhelming evidence of his past came into the public's eye, Ross later admitted that he did work as a correctional officer in Florida for 18 months between 1995 and 1997.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Burgess|first=Omar|title=Rick Ross Admits Correctional Officer past|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.7847/title.rick-ross-admits-correctional-officer-past|magazine=Hip Hop DX|date=October 7, 2008|accessdate=December 6, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201090640/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.7847/title.rick-ross-admits-correctional-officer-past|archivedate=December 1, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In a 2008 interview with AllHipHop.com,<ref>[http://allhiphop.com/stories/features/archive/2008/08/01/20354914.aspx]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090331072305/http://allhiphop.com/stories/features/archive/2008/08/01/20354914.aspx|date=March 31, 2009}}</ref> [[Ricky Ross (drug trafficker)|\"Freeway\" Ricky Ross]] claimed offense that Roberts used his name and identity when he learned that ''The Smoking Gun'' posted documents revealing Roberts' previous employment as a Florida correctional officer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thesmokinggun.com/archive/years/2008/0721081rickross1.html|title=Screw Rick Ross \u2013 TheSmokingGun.com|work=The Smoking Gun|accessdate=November 22, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100723013054/http://www.thesmokinggun.com/archive/years/2008/0721081rickross1.html|archivedate=July 23, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Seizures ===\nOn October 14, 2011, Ross suffered two seizures in the same day, once in the morning and again in the early evening. Following the morning seizure, he was unconscious and [[CPR]] was performed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.17238/title.rick-ross-suffers-seizure-on-plane-reportedly-regains-consciousness|title=Rick Ross Suffers Seizure On Plane, Reportedly Regains Consciousness|date=October 14, 2011|work=[[HipHopDX]]|accessdate=January 31, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150131211248/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.17238/title.rick-ross-suffers-seizure-on-plane-reportedly-regains-consciousness|archivedate=January 31, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> After suffering the second seizure, Ross was admitted to a hospital in [[Birmingham, Alabama]], where doctors ran a battery of tests. They declared him healthy. Ross attributes the episodes to a lack of sleep in the previous week.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/various-artists/60153|title=Rick Ross: 'Seizures were caused by me not getting enough sleep'|date=November 2, 2011|work=[[NME]] News|publisher=Time Inc|accessdate=January 31, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150131221017/http://www.nme.com/news/various-artists/60153|archivedate=January 31, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nRoss later noted the incident in the remix of [[Meek Mill]]'s song \"[[Ima Boss]]\", with the line \"Had a couple seizures, call it minor setbacks / Everybody praying for me, I respect that / Woke up in the hospital, where my checks at? / Then I put 8 chains where my neck's at\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rapfix.mtv.com/2011/11/09/meek-mill-ima-boss-remix-rick-ross-lil-wayne-ti-swizz-beatz/|title=Meek Mill Drops \u2018I\u2019ma Boss (Remix)\u2019 W/ Rick Ross, Lil Wayne, T.I., Swizz Beatz|author=Chandler, D.L.|publisher=MTV|date=November 9, 2011|accessdate=October 12, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120404035123/http://rapfix.mtv.com/2011/11/09/meek-mill-ima-boss-remix-rick-ross-lil-wayne-ti-swizz-beatz/|archivedate=April 4, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Drive-by shooting===\nOn January 27, 2013, while celebrating his 37th birthday, Ross and his girlfriend were the targets of a [[drive-by shooting]] in [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida]]. Neither Ross nor his girlfriend were hurt, but they ended up crashing their car into an apartment in an attempt to escape the shooting.<ref>{{cite web|last=Haskell |first=Josh |url=https://abcnews.go.com/blogs/entertainment/2013/01/rapper-rick-ross-target-of-drive-by-shooting/ |title=Rapper Rick Ross Target of Drive-By Shooting \u2013 ABC News |publisher=Abcnews.go.com |date=January 28, 2013 |accessdate=August 6, 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== 2018 hospitalization ===\nOn March 2, 2018, Ross was hospitalized after being found unresponsive in his Miami, Florida, home from a possible heart attack.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://people.com/music/rick-ross-unresponsive-florida-home/|title=Rick Ross Found Unresponsive After Emergency Crews Rush to His Miami Mansion: Report|author=|date=|website=people.com|accessdate=April 25, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180401084316/http://people.com/music/rick-ross-unresponsive-florida-home/|archivedate=April 1, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Ross was on life support.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/rick-ross-hooked-up-to-life-support-report/|title=Rick Ross Hooked Up to Life Support: Report|author=|date=March 2, 2018|website=usmagazine.com|accessdate=April 25, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180304061448/https://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/rick-ross-hooked-up-to-life-support-report/|archivedate=March 4, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He was released from hospital just a few days later.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pagesix.com/2018/05/16/rick-ross-is-living-life-to-the-fullest-following-health-woes/|title=Rick Ross is \"living life to the fullest\" following health woes|author=Derrick Taylor|date=May 16, 2018|website=pagesix.com|accessdate=June 14, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Family ===\nRoss has four children: Toie Roberts, William Roberts III, Berkeley Hermes Roberts, and Billion Leonard Roberts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://heavy.com/entertainment/2018/12/rick-ross-son-first-photo/|title=Rick Ross Shares First Photo of Son, Billion Leonard Roberts|last=Thompson|first=D.L.|date=December 10, 2018|website=[[Heavy.com]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thesource.com/2018/12/11/rick-ross-introduces-his-son-billion-on-instagram/|title=Rick Ross Introduces His Son Billion on Instragram|last=Grant|first=Shawn|date=December 11, 2018|website=The Source|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nRoss was briefly engaged to Lira \"Galore\" Mercer in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.vibe.com/2016/09/lira-galore-rick-ross-fix-my-life|title= Lira Galore Discusses Why She And Rick Ross Split On \"Fix My Life\"|work=Vibe}}</ref>\n\n== Legal issues ==\n[[File:Rick Ross mug shot.jpg|thumb|left|150px|[[Mug shot]] of Ross, 2008]]\nIn January 2008, Ross was arrested on gun and marijuana charges. During a deposition of Officer Rey Hernandez, a Miami Beach cop who arrested Ross, Ross's lawyer, Allan Zamren, asked Hernandez why Ross's case was assigned to the gang task force. The officer stated that it was because Ross claimed affiliation with [[Triple C's]] (aka Carol City Cartel), and other known gang members. Zamren pressed Hernandez for a personal link between Ross and the gang members, but the officer did not provide proof.<ref>{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Rick Ross' Own Lawyer De-Values |url=http://highbridnation.com/2009/02/10/rick-ross-own-lawyer-de-values-his-gangsta/ |publisher=Highbridnation.com |date=February 10, 2009 |accessdate=March 24, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090213102229/http://highbridnation.com/2009/02/10/rick-ross-own-lawyer-de-values-his-gangsta |archivedate=February 13, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nIn August 2008, YouTube entertainer [[DJ Vlad]] filed a lawsuit against Ross for assault and battery. Vlad claimed Ross organized an ambush on him at the 2008 Ozone Awards in [[Houston]], Texas for asking questions about his past as a correctional officer.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kaufman|first=Gil|title=DJ Vlad Files $4 Million Lawsuit Against Rick Ross Over Alleged Ozone Awards Beatdown|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1592890/20080815/ross__rick__rap_.jhtml|publisher=MTV News|date=August 15, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828040710/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1592890/20080815/ross__rick__rap_.jhtml|archivedate=August 28, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2010 \"Freeway\" Ricky Ross sued Ross for using his name,<ref name=\"Freeway Rick Ross sues Rick Ross\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.11543/title.freeway-ricky-ross-files-lawsuit-against-rapper-rick-ross|title=Freeway Rick Ross files lawsuit|last=Harling|first=Danielle|accessdate=June 25, 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140103035148/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.11543/title.freeway-ricky-ross-files-lawsuit-against-rapper-rick-ross|archivedate=January 3, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> filing a [[copyright infringement]] [[lawsuit]] in a California federal court.<ref name=\"Freeway Rick Ross sues Rick Ross\" /> [[Jay-Z]] had been called to testify in the lawsuit, as he was CEO of Def Jam when Ross/Roberts was signed.<ref name=\"Freeway Rick Ross sues Rick Ross\" /> \"Freeway\" Ricky Ross, a reformed drug kingpin, sought $10 million in damages in his lawsuit.<ref name=\"Freeway Rick Ross sues Rick Ross\" /> Also, Freeway Ricky Ross threatened to block the release of Ross' album, ''[[Teflon Don (album)|Teflon Don]].''\n\nA week after the lawsuit was filed, Rick Ross responded to the charges: \"It's like owning a restaurant, you're gonna have a few slip and falls. You get lawsuits, you deal with them, and get them out your way\u2026sometimes you lose.\"<ref name=\"Rapper Rick Ross Gets Legal Victory, Replies To $10 Mil Lawsuit\">{{cite web|url=http://allhiphop.com/stories/news/archive/2010/07/02/22284307.aspx|title=Rapper Rick Ross Gets Legal Victory, Replies To $10 Mil Lawsuit|last=Strong, Bostick|first=Nolan, Octavia|accessdate=September 12, 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100706145646/http://www.allhiphop.com/stories/news/archive/2010/07/02/22284307.aspx|archivedate=July 6, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He denied rumors that he would change his name to \"Ricky Rozay\" as a consequence of the lawsuit. The lawsuit was thrown out of court on July 3, 2010.<ref name=\"Freeway Ricky Ross' Lawsuit Against Rick Ross Thrown Out\">{{cite web|url=http://theurbandaily.com/gossip-news/billjohnson/freeway-ricky-ross-lawsuit-against-rick-ross-thrown-out/|title=Freeway Ricky Ross' Lawsuit Against Rick Ross Thrown Out|last=Johnson|first=Bill|accessdate=September 12, 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120312171244/http://theurbandaily.com/gossip-news/billjohnson/freeway-ricky-ross-lawsuit-against-rick-ross-thrown-out/|archivedate=March 12, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://nymag.com/daily/entertainment/2010/11/the_drug_dealer_rick_ross_has.html |magazine=New York Magazine |title=The Drug Dealer Rick Ross Has Lost His Lawsuit Against the Rapper Rick Ross |date=November 5, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111229053922/http://nymag.com/daily/entertainment/2010/11/the_drug_dealer_rick_ross_has.html |archivedate=2011-12-29 |url-status=live }}</ref> The album ''Teflon Don'' was released as scheduled on July 20, 2010.\n\nA federal judge ruled that the case should be refiled in California state court because it fell under California state law. \"Freeway\" Ricky Ross refiled the case with the State of California and the federal case is on appeal in the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit]].<ref name=\"Freeway Ricky Ross\u2019 Lawsuit Against Rick Ross Thrown Out\">{{cite web|url=http://theurbandaily.com/gossip-news/billjohnson/freeway-ricky-ross-lawsuit-against-rick-ross-thrown-out/ |title=Freeway Ricky Ross\u2019 Lawsuit Against Rick Ross Thrown Out |last=Johnson |first=Bill |accessdate=12 September 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120312171244/http://theurbandaily.com/gossip-news/billjohnson/freeway-ricky-ross-lawsuit-against-rick-ross-thrown-out/ |archivedate=2012-03-12 |url-status=live }}</ref> The state case was filed in 2011 in California.\n\n\"Freeway\" Ricky Ross refiled in Los Angeles Superior Court with publicity rights claims. Trial was set for early May 2012. The case was dismissed by a judge in the Los Angeles Superior Court.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rapfix.mtv.com/2012/02/29/freeway-rick-ross-court-date-with-rick-ross/ |title='Freeway' Rick Ross Will Take On Rick Ross In Court Early May |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140103030721/http://rapfix.mtv.com/2012/02/29/freeway-rick-ross-court-date-with-rick-ross/ |archivedate=2014-01-03 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe California State case was updated with a motion in Freeway Rick Ross' favor as to [[Warner Bros. Records]] and their use of the name and image Rick Ross in July 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/rick-ross-freeway-ricky-warner-bros-sue-maybach-music-351204 |title=Rick Ross Vs. Ricky \"Freeway\" Ross: Judge Rejects Warner Bros. Records' Motion to Dismiss |work=The Hollywood Reporter |first=Eriq |last=Gardner |date=2012-07-18 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130127180836/http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/industry/legal-and-management/rick-ross-vs-ricky-freeway-ross-judge-rejects-1007617352.story |archivedate=2013-01-27 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[New York Post]]'' reported that a trial was set for August 27, 2013 in Freeway Rick Ross versus Rick Ross and [[Warner Music Group]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/pagesix/rick_vs_rick_sBNa5IUgibTzmx7w3vfyqO |title=Rick Ross vs. Rick Ross: Rapper sued by drug trafficker for allegedly stealing name NY POST |work=New York Post |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130219031920/http://www.nypost.com/p/pagesix/rick_vs_rick_sBNa5IUgibTzmx7w3vfyqO |archivedate=2013-02-19 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn December 30, 2013, the court ruled in favor of the rapper Rick Ross, allowing him to keep the name based on a [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]] ruling.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/freeway-ricky-ross-rick-ross-667879 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |first=Eriq |last=Gardner |title='Freeway' Ricky Ross vs. Rick Ross: First Amendment Protects Hip-Hop Persona |date=2013-12-30 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140309134858/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/freeway-ricky-ross-rick-ross-667879 |archivedate=2014-03-09 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, the rapper Teflon Don filed a [[trademark infringement]] lawsuit against Ross for the use of the name as an album title.<ref name=\"Memphis Rap 2011-08-29\">{{cite news|url=http://www.memphisrap.com/2011/08/29/exclusive-rick-ross-dj-khaled-def-jam-named-in-infringement-lawsuit-by-teflon-don/|title=Freeway Exclusive: Rick Ross, DJ Khaled, Def Jam Named In Infringement Lawsuit by Teflon Don|date=August 29, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Rick Ross, DJ Khaled & More Being Sued for 'Teflon Don' Name\">{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/467680/rick-ross-dj-khaled-more-being-sued-for-teflon-don-name|title=Rick Ross, DJ Khaled & More Being Sued for 'Teflon Don' Name|last=Ramirez|first=Erika|date=August 29, 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130316052136/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/467680/rick-ross-dj-khaled-more-being-sued-for-teflon-don-name|archivedate=March 16, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn March 26, 2011, Ross was arrested in Shreveport for possession of [[marijuana]]. According to the police records, a strong odor of marijuana was detected from his room at the Hilton in Downtown Shreveport.<ref>{{cite news |author=Clemons, Tracy |title=Rapper and NFL star separately arrested in Shreveport |url=http://www.ksla.com/Global/story.asp?S=14326804 |work=ksla.com |date=March 26, 2011 |accessdate=March 27, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307171443/http://www.ksla.com/Global/story.asp?S=14326804 |archivedate=March 7, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Ross was arrested on June 27, 2014, in Greensboro, N.C., following his performance at the 2014 SuperJam at the Greensboro Coliseum. The arrest stemmed from a year-old warrant for another North Carolina arrest related to marijuana possession; Ross reportedly failed to appear in court for that violation in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rick Ross Arrested in North Carolina on Outstanding Warrant|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/6141058/rick-ross-arrested-in-north-carolina-on-outstanding-warrant|website=billboard|accessdate=20 February 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150617215342/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/6141058/rick-ross-arrested-in-north-carolina-on-outstanding-warrant|archivedate=June 17, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn June 24, 2015, Rick Ross and his bodyguard were arrested in [[Fayette County, Georgia]] on kidnapping and assault charges. Both were accused for forcing a lands keeper into a guesthouse and beating him in the head with a handgun, allegedly over money he owed Ross.<ref>{{cite web|title=RICK ROSS ARRESTED FOR KIDNAPPING ASSAULT|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/cheats/2015/06/24/rick-ross-booked-for-kidnapping-assault.html|website=The Daily Beast|accessdate=25 June 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150627061347/http://www.thedailybeast.com/cheats/2015/06/24/rick-ross-booked-for-kidnapping-assault.html|archivedate=June 27, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Rapper Rick Ross Arrested on Kidnapping, Assault Charges|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/wireStory/rapper-rick-ross-arrested-kidnapping-assault-charges-31990584|website=abc News|accessdate=25 June 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20140414003650/http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/wireStory/rapper-rick-ross-arrested-kidnapping-assault-charges-31990584|archivedate=April 14, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Rick Ross Arrested on Kidnapping, Assault Charges|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6605814/rick-ross-arrested-kidnapping-assault-charges?mobile_redirection=false|website=Billboard|accessdate=25 June 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150628194629/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6605814/rick-ross-arrested-kidnapping-assault-charges?mobile_redirection=false|archivedate=June 28, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On April 4, 2017, Ross pled no contest to a felony count of aggravated assault. The other felony charges were dropped. Ross was sentenced to time served in jail, having already been incarcerated for a week and was also ordered to pay a $10,000 fine.\n\nRoss was sentenced as a first time felony offender; and upon payment of the fine the conviction was erased from his record. Ross pled no contest to 5 misdemeanours; of assault, battery, two counts of pointing a pistol at someone, and possession of less than 1 oz of cannabis. For the five misdemeanours he was given a total of 60 months probation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://amp.tmz.com/2017/04/04/rick-ross-plea-deal-kidnapping-case|title=RICK ROSS GETS SWEET PLEA DEAL IN KIDNAPPING CASE|last=|first=|date=|website=TMZ|accessdate=20 February 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180221043214/http://amp.tmz.com/2017/04/04/rick-ross-plea-deal-kidnapping-case|archivedate=February 21, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Business ventures ==\nAs of 2017, Ross owned several different [[Wingstop]] restaurant locations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allhiphop.com/news/rick-ross-opens-new-wingstop-in-decatur-CNThR45fgUqPu0pRcbE4rQ/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170322204046/https://allhiphop.com/2017/01/26/rick-ross-opens-new-wingstop-decatur/|url-status=dead|title=Rick Ross Opens New Wingstop In Decatur|archivedate=March 22, 2017|website=AllHipHop.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thesource.com/2016/07/04/rick-ross-makes-big-moves-to-expand-his-franchise/|title=Rick Ross Makes Big Moves To Expand His Franchise - The Source|author=|date=July 4, 2016|website=thesource.com|accessdate=April 25, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201030620/http://thesource.com/2016/07/04/rick-ross-makes-big-moves-to-expand-his-franchise/|archivedate=December 1, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Wingstop is fast food chain, specialising in chicken wings.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wingstop |title=About Us |url=https://www.wingstop.com/about-us |website=Wingstop |accessdate= May 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Controversy ==\n===Feud with 50 Cent===\nIn January 2009, Ross started a feud with rapper [[50 Cent]] because he supposedly looked at him the wrong way at the [[BET Hip Hop Awards]] in 2008. 50 Cent told news sources that he did not remember seeing Ross there.<ref>{{cite news|title=How feud Started Rick Ross and 50 Cent |url=http://www.vibe.com/news/news_headlines/2009/01/50_cent_vs_rick_ross_video/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090203122223/http://www.vibe.com/news/news_headlines/2009/01/50_cent_vs_rick_ross_video/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 3, 2009 |publisher=Vide.com |date=February 7, 2009 |accessdate=March 16, 2009 }}</ref> In late January, \"Mafia Music\", by Ross, leaked onto the Internet. There were several lines that seemed to diss 50 Cent. Days later, 50 Cent released \"Officer Ricky (Go Head, Try Me)\" in response to Ross's disparaging remarks on his \"Mafia Music\" song.\n\nBefore going to [[Venezuela]], 50 Cent uploaded a video entitled \"Warning Shot\", wherein he stated: \"Rick Ross- I'mma fuck your life up for fun.\" In addition, 50 Cent released the first of a series of \"Officer Ricky\" cartoons. Early in February, 50 Cent once again made a video which he uploaded to YouTube in which he interviewed \"Tia\", the mother of one of Ross's children. She verifies that he was a correctional officer and claims his whole persona is fake and fraudulent.<ref>[http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/videos/id.2138 HipHopDX.com \u2013 50 Cent \u2013 Interviews Rick Ross' Baby Mama] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121001091702/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/videos/id.2138 |date=October 1, 2012 }}. ''HipHopDX.com''. Accessed February 2, 2008.</ref> On February 5, 2009, [[The Game (rapper)|The Game]], who 50 Cent has a long-standing \"beef\" with, called up [[Seattle]] R&B station [[KUBE (FM)|KUBE]]. When asked about the beef between 50 Cent and Ross, Game sided with 50 Cent and said that things are not looking good for Ross. He offered to help, stating, \"Rick Ross, holla at your boy, man,\" and, \"50 eating you, boy.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1604407/20090205/ross__rick__rap_.jhtml|title=Game Takes Sides In 50 Cent|work=MTV News|accessdate=November 22, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090823024332/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1604407/20090205/ross__rick__rap_.jhtml|archivedate=August 23, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\nOn his album ''[[Deeper Than Rap]]'', Ross references 50 Cent in the song \"In Cold Blood\". A video for the song was released that portrayed 50 Cent's mock funeral. Upon release, Ross stated that he has ended 50 Cent's career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1609554/20090420/ross__rick__rap_.jhtml|title=Rick Ross Buries 50 Cent In 'Cold Blood'|work=MTV News|accessdate=November 22, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090721093932/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1609554/20090420/ross__rick__rap_.jhtml|archivedate=July 21, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref> That same day Ross released a new diss track called \"Push 'Em Over The Edge\". The next day 50 Cent released the controversial video \"A Psychic Told Me\", dissing [[DJ Khaled]]. On February 12, 50 Cent responded with \"Tia Told Me\", along with Lloyd Banks' response \"Officer Down\" and Tony Yayo's \"Somebody Snitched\".\n\nIn an interview, 50 Cent said Ross is \"Albert From ''[[CB4]]''. You ever seen the movie? He's Albert,\" he added. \"It never gets worse than this. You get a guy that was a correctional officer come out and base his entire career on writing material from a drug dealer's perspective.\"<ref>[http://www.ballerstatus.com/2009/03/03/50-cent-says-rick-ross-is-gusto-from-cb4-laughs-off-ross-sales-predictions/ 50 Cent Says Rick Ross Is 'Gusto From CB4', Laughs Off Ross' Sales Predictions] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100619085851/http://www.ballerstatus.com/2009/03/03/50-cent-says-rick-ross-is-gusto-from-cb4-laughs-off-ross-sales-predictions/ |date=June 19, 2010 }} BallerStatus.com</ref>\n\nOn January 30, 2013, 50 Cent claimed via Twitter that the drive-by shooting that Ross experienced on his birthday two days ago was \"staged\", reigniting the feud.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sieczkowski|first=Cavan|title=50 Cent Claims Rick Ross Shooting Was 'Staged'|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/01/30/50-cent-rick-ross-shooting-staged_n_2581245.html|newspaper=[[Huffington Post]]|date=January 30, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130209200009/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/01/30/50-cent-rick-ross-shooting-staged_n_2581245.html|archivedate=February 9, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nA year later, on March 28, 2014, Rick Ross was asked about his feud with 50 Cent. He stated that he doesn't wish to speak on him anymore, and that he's done with the feud.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Harling|first=Danielle|title=Rick Ross \"Through Talking About\" 50 Cent|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.28096/title.rick-ross-through-talking-about-50-cent|magazine=HipHopDX|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140401123036/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.28096/title.rick-ross-through-talking-about-50-cent|archivedate=April 1, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nHis feud with 50 Cent has been resurfacing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/meek-mill-disses-50-cent-on-gave-em-hope-news.19660.html|title=50 Cent and Rick Ross beef resurfacing|publisher=Hotnewhiphop.com|date=January 16, 2016|accessdate=January 17, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160119185111/http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/meek-mill-disses-50-cent-on-gave-em-hope-news.19660.html|archivedate=January 19, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The reason of the second reignition would be because of Ross' MMG record-label artist [[Meek Mill]], who defended his mentor and called out 50 on his ''4/4'' EP.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.rap-up.com/2016/02/01/50-cent-disses-meek-mill-at-nyc-show/ |title=50 Cent Disses Meek Mill: \u2018All You Can Do Is Run to Nicki\u2019 |magazine=Rap-Up |accessdate=2017-03-15 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170415142357/http://www.rap-up.com/2016/02/01/50-cent-disses-meek-mill-at-nyc-show/ |archivedate=April 15, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Lyric controversy===\nIn a line on rapper [[Rocko (rapper)|Rocko]]'s 2013 song \"[[U.O.E.N.O.]]\", Rick Ross raps the line, \"Put molly all in her champagne/ She ain't even know it/ I took her home and I enjoyed that/ She ain't even know it.\" A petition containing 72,000 signatures was presented to [[Reebok]], demanding they drop Ross as a spokesman for the lyrics which appeared to condone [[date rape]]. Ross has apologized for the lyrics, claiming they weren't about rape.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.3news.co.nz/Rick-Ross-rape-lyric-apology-not-accepted/tabid/418/articleID/293110/Default.aspx| work= 3 News NZ| title= Rick Ross rape lyric apology not accepted| date= April 5, 2013| url-status=live| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20131224121936/http://www.3news.co.nz/Rick-Ross-rape-lyric-apology-not-accepted/tabid/418/articleID/293110/Default.aspx| archivedate= December 24, 2013| df= mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn April 11, 2013, one month after the song's release, Ross was dropped by Reebok.<ref>{{cite news|title=RICK ROSS REEBOK GIVES RAPPER THE BOOT|url=https://www.tmz.com/2013/04/11/reebok-dumps-rick-ross-drops/|work=TMZ|accessdate=April 11, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130413111416/http://www.tmz.com/2013/04/11/reebok-dumps-rick-ross-drops/|archivedate=April 13, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Reebok stated, \u201cwhile we do not believe that Rick Ross condones sexual assault, we are very disappointed he has yet to display an understanding of the seriousness of this issue or an appropriate level of remorse.\u201d  They continued on to say, \u201cat this time, it is in everyone\u2019s best interest for Reebok to end its partnership with Mr. Ross.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/rick-ross-loses-reebok-endorsement-over-rape-lyrics-233402/|title=Rick Ross Loses Reebok Endorsement Over \u2018Rape\u2019 Lyrics|last=Danton|first=Eric|date=April 12, 2013|website=Rolling Stone|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=May 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/apr/12/rick-ross-loses-reebok-deal|title=Rick Ross loses Reebok deal over 'date rape' verse|last=|first=|date=2013|website=The Guardian|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=May 7, 2019}}</ref>\u201d\n\nThough Ross apologized for the lyrics, he also argued that his lyrics were misinterpreted because he did not directly use the word \u201crape.\u201d He says, \u201cYou know I would never use the term rape in my records\u2026 in reality some people do these things, and shouldn\u2019t it be brought to light so young women can protect themselves?!\u201d  He continued on Twitter, \"I would never use the term \u2018rape\u2019 in my records and as far as my camp.  Hip-Hop don't condone that, the streets don't condone that, nobody condones that.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/6wg4y6/question-of-the-day-is-rick-ross-a-misogynist|title=Question Of The Day - Is Rick Ross a Misogynist?|last=Gadiano|first=Jerry|date=April 15, 2013|website=Vice|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=May 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nA 2013 Ross concert organized by the student association of [[Carleton University]] was cancelled after protests that his lyrics promote [[rape culture]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.charlatan.ca/2013/04/former-cusa-prez-running-company-behind-rick-ross-concert/ |title=Rick Ross concert completely cancelled following criticism &#124; Charlatan |publisher=Charlatan.ca |date= |accessdate=August 6, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523093356/http://charlatan.ca/2013/04/former-cusa-prez-running-company-behind-rick-ross-concert/ |archivedate=May 23, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Rocko later dropped the Rick Ross verse in order to get radio play.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.3news.co.nz/Rocko-replaces-Rick-Ross-rap/tabid/418/articleID/293956/Default.aspx| work= 3 News NZ| title= Rocko replaces Rick Ross rap| date= April 12, 2013| url-status=live| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140102193644/http://www.3news.co.nz/Rocko-replaces-Rick-Ross-rap/tabid/418/articleID/293956/Default.aspx| archivedate= January 2, 2014| df= mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Comment on female rappers ===\nIn 2017, Ross was criticized for stating in an interview that he never signed a female rapper because \"I would end up fucking [her] and fucking the business up.\"<ref name=mistake>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/rick-ross-insensitive-comments-about-female-rappers-were-mistake-195084/|title=Rick Ross: 'Insensitive' Comments About Female Rappers Were 'Mistake'|last=Reed|first=Ryan|last2=Reed|first2=Ryan|date=2017-07-28|website=Rolling Stone|access-date=2019-05-02}}</ref> Ross quickly apologized through a Facebook post where he called his comments \"insensitive\" and a \"mistake [he regrets].\"<ref name=mistake />\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Rick Ross discography|Triple C's discography}} <!-- Per [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians/Article guidelines]], The discography section of the musician's primary article should \"provide a summary of the musician's major works. In most cases this is done using a simple list of their studio albums, leaving a complete listing of releases to the discography article.\" -->\n\n'''Studio albums'''\n* ''[[Port of Miami (album)|Port of Miami]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Trilla]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Deeper Than Rap]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Teflon Don (album)|Teflon Don]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[God Forgives, I Don't]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Mastermind (Rick Ross album)|Mastermind]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Hood Billionaire]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Black Market (Rick Ross album)|Black Market]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Rather You Than Me]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Port of Miami 2]]'' (2019)<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://hiphopdx.com/news/id.42799/title.rick-ross-announces-new-album-no-not-rather-you-than-me|title=Rick Ross Announces New Album|magazine=HipHopDX|accessdate=March 22, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170322071126/http://hiphopdx.com/news/id.42799/title.rick-ross-announces-new-album-no-not-rather-you-than-me|archivedate=March 22, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n'''Collaborative albums'''\n*''[[Custom Cars & Cycles]]'' <small>(with [[Triple C's]])</small> (2009)\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Type\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Days of Wrath]]''\n| Film\n| G Dogg\n| \n|-\n| 2008\u20132012\n| ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]''\n| Television\n| rowspan=\"4\"|Himself\n| rowspan=\"4\"|Musical guest\n|-\n| 2009\n